text: Autosomal Dominant Osteopetrosis 2 is classified as a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal dominant disease, a spinal disease, and a specific form of osteopetrosis. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is associated with symptoms such as abscesses. The disease primarily affects the vertebral column. It is defined as an osteopetrosis that features autosomal dominant inheritance, resulting in sclerosis predominantly involving the spine, the pelvis, and the skull base, along with bone fragility and dental abscesses, due to a mutation in the CLCN7 gene on chromosome 16p13. Moreover, it is known by several exact synonyms including Albers-Schonberg osteopetrosis, OPTA2, autosomal dominant Albers-Schonberg disease, autosomal dominant osteopetrosis type II, and osteopetrosis autosomal dominant type 2.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 5, which has the exact synonyms OPTB5 and infantile malignant osteopetrosis 3, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, osteopetrosis, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance that has its material basis in a mutation in the OSTM1 gene on chromosome 6q21.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 8 (OPTB8) is a type of osteopetrosis and a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance and has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this form of osteopetrosis is caused by a homozygous mutation in the SNX10 gene on chromosome 7p15.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 3 is a type of disease characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, and it falls under the category of osteopetrosis diseases. It is specifically associated with having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as an osteopetrosis that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CA2 gene located on chromosome 8q21. Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 3 is known by several exact synonyms, including Guibaud-Vainsel syndrome, OPTB3, autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 3 with renal tubular acidosis, carbonic anhydrase II deficiency, marble brain disease, and osteopetrosis with renal tubular acidosis.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 1 is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal recessive disease, a type of osteopetrosis, and a condition that inherently involves autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TCIRG1 gene located on chromosome 11q13.2. Additionally, autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 1 is known by exact synonyms, including OPTB1, autosomal recessive Albers-Schonberg disease, and infantile malignant osteopetrosis 1.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, and it is also classified as a type of osteopetrosis. This condition falls under the category of diseases that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance that is the result of a homozygous mutation in the TNFSF11 gene located on chromosome 13q14. Furthermore, autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 2 is known by several exact synonyms, including OPTB2, mild autosomal recessive form osteopetrosis, and osteoclast-poor osteopetrosis.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, osteopetrosis, and a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CLCN7 gene on chromosome 16p13. Additionally, autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 4 is exactly synonymous with OPTB4 and infantile malignant osteopetrosis 2.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 6 (OPTB6) is a type of disease that falls under three categories: autosomal recessive disease, osteopetrosis, and diseases that fundamentally have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically characterized by an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern that is due to a mutation in the PLEKHM1 gene located on chromosome 17q21.31. Additionally, it is precisely known by another name, the autosomal recessive osteopetrosis intermediate form, indicating its exact synonymy with OPTB6.

Autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 7 is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the category of osteopetrosis. It is associated with autosomal recessive inheritance, implying that it arises due to a material basis in this type of heredity. Specifically, autosomal recessive osteopetrosis 7 is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, which is a result of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TNFRSF11A gene located on chromosome 18q21. Furthermore, this condition is known by several exact synonyms including OPTB7, autosomal recessive osteoclast-poor osteopetrosis with hypogammaglobulinemia, autosomal recessive osteopetrosis type 7, osteoclast-poor osteopetrosis with hypogammaglobulinemia, and osteopetrosis-hypogammaglobulinemia syndrome.

Waardenburg Syndrome Type 2B, which is a form of Waardenburg Syndrome, is characterized by pigmentary abnormalities of the hair, skin, and eyes, congenital sensorineural hearing loss, and the absence of lateral displacement of the inner canthus of each eye. This condition has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 1p21-p13.3. Additionally, Waardenburg Syndrome Type 2B is precisely referred to as WS2B and Waardenburg Syndrome Type IIB.

Waardenburg syndrome type 1 is a form of Waardenburg syndrome characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of congenital deafness, pigmentation anomalies of eyes, hair, and skin, and dystopia canthorum. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the PAX3 gene located on chromosome 2q36. Additionally, Waardenburg syndrome type 1 is exactly synonymous with both WS1 and Waardenburg syndrome type I.

Waardenburg Syndrome Type 3, also known precisely as Klein-Waardenburg Syndrome, WS3, and Waardenburg Syndrome Type III, is a specific variant of Waardenburg Syndrome. This syndrome is characterized by a combination of upper limb anomalies, congenital hearing loss, dystopia canthorum, and pigmentation anomalies affecting the eyes, hair, and skin. These characteristics are due to either heterozygous or homozygous mutations in the PAX3 gene located on chromosome 2q36. Another exact synonym for Waardenburg Syndrome Type 3 is Waardenburg Syndrome with upper limb anomalies.

Waardenburg Syndrome Type 2A (WS2A), also known exactly as Waardenburg Syndrome Type IIA, is a specific kind of Waardenburg Syndrome and a type of digenic disease, which means it is a type of condition that has at least a material basis in some form of digenic inheritance. It is characterized by pigmentary abnormalities of the hair, skin, and eyes, congenital sensorineural hearing loss, and the absence of lateral displacement of the inner canthus of each eye, stemming from a heterozygous mutation in the MITF gene on chromosome 3p13.

Waardenburg syndrome type 2C, also known exactly as WS2C and Waardenburg syndrome type IIC, is a type of Waardenburg syndrome. It is characterized by pigmentary abnormalities of the hair, skin, and eyes, congenital sensorineural hearing loss, and the absence of lateral displacement of the inner canthus of each eye. This condition has a material basis in variation in the chromosome region 8p23.

Waardenburg Syndrome Type 4A is a type of Waardenburg Syndrome characterized by pigmentary abnormalities of the hair, skin, and eyes, congenital sensorineural hearing loss, and Hirschsprung disease. This condition has its material basis in either heterozygous or homozygous mutations in the EDNRB gene located on chromosome 13q22. It is exactly synonymous with WS4A, Waardenburg Syndrome Type IVA, and Waardenburg Syndrome with Hirschsprung Disease Type 4A.

Waardenburg syndrome type 4B, also precisely known as WS4B, Waardenburg syndrome type IVB, and Waardenburg syndrome with Hirschsprung disease type 4B, is a specific form of Waardenburg syndrome. It is characterized by pigmentary abnormalities of the hair, skin, and eyes, congenital sensorineural hearing loss, and Hirschsprung disease. This condition has its material basis in both homozygous and heterozygous mutations in the EDN3 gene located on chromosome 20q13.

Waardenburg syndrome type 4C, also known exactly as WS4C, Waardenburg syndrome type IVC, and Waardenburg syndrome with Hirschsprung disease type 4C, is a type of Waardenburg syndrome. It is characterized by pigmentary abnormalities of the hair, skin, and eyes, congenital sensorineural hearing loss, and Hirschsprung disease. This specific syndrome has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SOX10 gene located on chromosome 22q13.

Waardenburg syndrome type 2E, which is a type of Waardenburg syndrome, is characterized by pigmentary abnormalities of the hair, skin, and eyes, congenital sensorineural hearing loss, and the absence of lateral displacement of the inner canthus of each eye. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the SOX10 gene on chromosome 22q13. It is exactly synonymized with WS2E, WS2E with or without neurological involvement, Waardenburg syndrome type 2E with or without neurologic involvement, Waardenburg syndrome type IIE, and hypogonadotropic hypogonadism with anosmia and deafness with or without hypopigmentation.

Gaucher's disease type I is a specific form of Gaucher's disease and falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a type of Gaucher's disease characterized by the absence of primary central nervous system involvement, with its material basis being either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GBA1 gene located on chromosome 1q22. Additionally, Gaucher's disease type I is known by several exact synonyms, including Acid Beta-Glucosidase Deficiency, GD I, GD1, Gaucher Disease, Noncerebral Juvenile, Gba Deficiency, and Glucocerebrosidase Deficiency.

Gaucher's disease type II is a type of Gaucher's disease and also a type of something that at least disease has a basis in some structural variant. It is characterized by rapid neurologic deterioration with cranial nerve and extrapyramidal tract involvement that is based on homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GBA1 gene on chromosome 1q22. Additionally, Gaucher's disease type II has several exact synonyms, including GD II, GD2, Gaucher Disease, Acute Neuronopathic Type, and Infantile Cerebral Gaucher Disease.

Gaucher's Disease Type III is a type of Gaucher's Disease and an autosomal recessive disease that has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a later onset and slower progression of neurological deterioration compared to Type II, with this condition having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GBA1 gene on chromosome 1q22. Gaucher's Disease Type III has exact synonyms, including GD III, Gaucher Disease, Chronic Neuronopathic Type, Gaucher Disease, Juvenile and Adult, Cerebral, and Gaucher Disease, Subacute Neuronopathic Type.

Gaucher's disease perinatal lethal is a type of Gaucher's disease, which is also a type of disease that has its basis in some structural variant. It is characterized by perinatal lethality and rapid progression of neurological deterioration that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GBA1 gene on chromosome 1q22. This condition is exactly synonymous with both Fetal Gaucher Disease and Gaucher Disease, Collodion Type.

Atypical Gaucher's disease due to saposin C deficiency is a type of Gaucher's disease and also a type of condition that has its basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a Gaucher's disease that has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the PSAP gene on chromosome 10q22.1.

Brachydactyly preaxial hallux varus syndrome is a type of brachydactyly characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of short thumbs and first toes with abduction of these digits. This shortening involves the metacarpals, metatarsals, and distal phalanges. It is also known by its exact synonyms, Christian brachydactyly and preaxial brachydactyly with hallux varus and thumb abduction.

Ballard syndrome is a type of brachydactyly, which is defined as a brachydactyly characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of hypoplasia of the distal phalanges of the ulnar side of the hand and shortening of one or more metacarpals but normal stature. Furthermore, Ballard syndrome has exact synonyms including Ballard type brachydactyly, Pitt-Williams brachydactyly, and brachydactyly types B and E combined.

Brachydactyly type A1 is a type of brachydactyly and an autosomal dominant disease, which has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a brachydactyly characterized by rudimentary or fused middle phalanges of all the digits and shortened proximal phalanges of the thumbs and big toes. Additionally, Brachydactyly type A1 has exact synonyms, including BDA1 and Farabee type brachydactyly.

Brachydactyly type A2 is a type of Brachydactyly and an autosomal dominant disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is specifically characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of malformations of the middle phalanx of the index finger and anomalies of the second toe, with its material basis in heterozygous mutations in the BMPR1B gene on chromosome 4q or in the GDF5 gene on chromosome 20q11, or heterozygous duplication in a regulatory element of BMP2 on chromosome 20p12. Additionally, it has exact synonyms, including BDA2, Mohr-Wriedt type Brachydactyly, and brachymesophalangy II.

Brachydactyly type A3 is a type of brachydactyly characterized by the shortening of the middle phalanx of the fifth finger, which results in the radial curvature of the fifth finger. It has exact synonyms: BDA3, brachydactyly-clinodactyly, and brachymesophalangy V.

Brachydactyly type A4 is a type of brachydactyly characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of hypoplastic middle phalanges, brachymesophalangy affecting mainly the 2nd and 5th digits, and congenital talipes calcaneovalgus. It has exact synonyms including BDA4, Temtamy type brachydactyly, and brachymesophalangy II and V.

Brachydactyly Type A6 is a type of brachydactyly characterized by brachymesophalangy with mesomelic short limbs, absence or hypoplasia of second phalanges with synostosis of the remaining phalanges, and carpal and tarsal coalitions. It has exact synonyms including BDA6, Osebold-Remondini syndrome, and brachymesophalangy with mesomelic short limbs and carpal and tarsal osseous abnormalities.

Brachydactyly type B1 is a type of brachydactyly that is characterized by short middle phalanges, rudimentary or absent terminal phalanges, and nail aplasia. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ROR2 gene located on chromosome 9q22. It is also exactly synonymous with BDB1.

Brachydactyly type C (BDC) is a type of brachydactyly and also an autosomal dominant disease, which specifically has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a brachydactyly characterized by rachymesophalangy of the index, middle, and little fingers, hyperphalangy of the index and middle finger, and the shortening of the 1st metacarpal, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the GDF5 gene on chromosome 20q11.

Brachydactyly type D is a type of brachydactyly and an autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by short and broad terminal phalanges of the thumbs and big toes, a condition that arises from a mutation in the HOXD13 gene on chromosome 2q31.1. Furthermore, Brachydactyly type D is exactly synonymous with BDD.

Brachydactyly type E1 is a type of brachydactyly characterized by the shortening of the fingers, mainly in the metacarpals and metatarsals. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the HOXD13 gene on chromosome 2q31. It is also exactly synonymous with BDE1.

Mononen Karnes Senac syndrome is a type of brachydactyly and is characterized by short, abducted thumbs and great toes. This syndrome affects areas where the foot and finger intersect. It is also known by its exact synonyms, Mononen type brachydactyly and short and abducted thumbs and great toes.

Brachydactyly type A1B, which is a type of Brachydactyly type A1, is characterized by shortened middle phalanges of all digits and shortened proximal phalanges of the thumbs and big toes but normal stature, and this condition has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 5p13.3-p13.2. Furthermore, Brachydactyly type A1B is a type of condition that at least has its basis in some structural variant. It also has the exact synonym BDA1B.

Brachydactyly type B2 is a type of brachydactyly and has an exact synonym BDB2. It is characterized by hypoplasia/aplasia of distal phalanges, distal symphalangism, fusion of carpal/tarsal bones, and partial cutaneous syndactyly. This condition has a material basis in mutations in the NOG gene located on chromosome 17q22.

Brachydactyly type E2, which is a type of brachydactyly, is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of short stature, tooth abnormalities, and short metacarpals and metatarsals. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PTHLH gene on chromosome 12p. Brachydactyly type E2 is also exactly synonymous with BDE2.

Brachydactyly Type A1C, which is also exactly known as BDA1C, is a specific type of Brachydactyly Type A1. It falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. The definition of Brachydactyly Type A1C specifies that it is a Brachydactyly type A1 which has its material basis in either homozygous or heterozygous mutation in the GDF5 gene located on chromosome 20q11.

Brachydactyly type A1D is a subtype of brachydactyly type A1, and it is also classified as a type of condition that is fundamentally based on some structural variant. This particular condition, brachydactyly type A1D, is defined as a brachydactyly type A1 with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BMPR1B gene located on chromosome 4q22. Additionally, brachydactyly type A1D is exactly synonymous with BDA1D.

Sugarman brachydactyly is a type of brachydactyly that is also categorized as a kind of disease located in the foot. It is defined as a brachydactyly characterized by a nonarticulating great toe set dorsal and proximal to the typical position. Additionally, Sugarman brachydactyly has the exact synonym "brachydactyly with major proximal phalangeal shortening."

Joubert syndrome 1 is a type of Joubert syndrome with a definition specifying that it is a Joubert syndrome having its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the INPP5E gene located on chromosome 9q34. It has exact synonyms including CORS1, CPD4, JBTS1, cerebellooculorenal syndrome 1, and cerebelloparenchymal disorder IV.

Joubert syndrome 10 is a type of Joubert syndrome and is also classified as a type of X-linked recessive disease, which implies it is a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, Joubert syndrome 10 is defined as a Joubert syndrome that has its material basis in the X-linked recessive inheritance of a mutation in the OFD1 gene located on chromosome Xp22.2. Additionally, Joubert syndrome 10 is exactly synonymous with JBTS10.

Joubert syndrome 13 is a type of Joubert syndrome and has the exact synonym JBTS13. It is defined as a Joubert syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TCTN1 gene on chromosome 12q24.

Joubert syndrome 14 is a type of Joubert syndrome characterized by severe mental retardation, hypoplasia of the cerebellar vermis, and a molar tooth sign on brain imaging, hypotonia, an abnormal breathing pattern in infancy, and dysmorphic facial features. This specific syndrome has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TMEM237 gene on chromosome 2q33. Joubert syndrome 14 is also exactly synonymous with JBTS14.

Joubert syndrome 15 is a type of Joubert syndrome and a type of digenic disease, which is something that at least has a material basis in some digenic inheritance. It is characterized by ataxia, hypotonia, delayed psychomotor development, and variable mental retardation due to a homozygous mutation in the CEP41 gene on chromosome 7q32. Additionally, Joubert syndrome 15 has the exact synonym JBTS15.

Joubert syndrome 16 is a type of Joubert syndrome, which is defined as a Joubert syndrome characterized by the molar tooth sign on brain imaging, oculomotor apraxia, variable coloboma, and rare kidney involvement. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the TMEM138 gene on chromosome 11q. It also has the exact synonym JBTS16.

Joubert syndrome 17 is a type of Joubert syndrome and has an exact synonym JBTS17. It is defined as a Joubert syndrome characterized by episodic hyperpnea, abnormal eye movements, ataxia, and global psychomotor retardation. This condition has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the C5ORF42 gene on chromosome 5p13.

Joubert syndrome 18 is a type of Joubert syndrome that has the exact synonym JBTS18. It is defined as a Joubert syndrome that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the TCTN3 gene on chromosome 10q24.

Joubert syndrome 2 is a specific type of Joubert syndrome characterized by a molar tooth sign on brain MRI, hypotonia, developmental delay, oculomotor apraxia, and breathing abnormalities. This syndrome has its material basis in a mutation in the TMEM216 gene located on chromosome 11q12.2. It is precisely known by several synonyms, including CORS2, JBTS2, and cerebellooculorenal syndrome 2.

Joubert Syndrome 20 is a type of Joubert Syndrome and it is exactly synonymous with JBTS20. This particular syndrome is defined as a Joubert syndrome that has its material basis in a compound heterozygous mutation in the TMEM231 gene located on chromosome 16q23.

Joubert Syndrome 21 is a type of Joubert Syndrome, which is defined by a Joubert syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CSPP1 gene on chromosome 8q13. Additionally, it has the exact synonym JBTS21.

Joubert syndrome 22 is a type of Joubert syndrome and is exactly synonymous with JBTS22. It is defined as a Joubert syndrome that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the PDE6D gene on chromosome 2q37.

Joubert Syndrome 23 is a type of Joubert Syndrome characterized by delayed development, abnormal eye movements, and an abnormal breathing pattern. It is also identified by the molar tooth sign on brain MRI. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KIAA0586 gene on chromosome 14q23. Additionally, Joubert Syndrome 23 has the exact synonym JBTS23.

Joubert syndrome 24 is a type of Joubert syndrome characterized by delayed psychomotor development and the presence of a molar tooth sign on brain MRI. This specific condition, which is also exactly known as JBTS24, has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the TCTN2 gene located on chromosome 12q24.

Joubert syndrome 25 is a type of Joubert syndrome, characterized by delayed psychomotor development, oculomotor apraxia, and the molar tooth sign visible on brain MRI. This specific syndrome, also known exactly as JBTS25, has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CEP104 gene located on chromosome 1p36.

Joubert Syndrome 26 is a type of Joubert Syndrome, characterized by global developmental delay and cerebellar hypoplasia. This condition has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the KIAA0556 gene located on chromosome 16p12. It is also exactly synonymous with JBTS26.

Joubert syndrome 27 is a type of Joubert syndrome and is exactly synonymous with JBTS27. It is defined as a Joubert syndrome that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the B9D1 gene on chromosome 17p11.

Joubert syndrome 28 is a type of Joubert syndrome with the exact synonym JBTS28. It is defined as a Joubert syndrome that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MKS1 gene on chromosome 17q23.

Joubert syndrome 3 is a type of Joubert syndrome and is exactly synonymous with JBTS3. It is defined as a Joubert syndrome that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the AHI1 gene on chromosome 6q23.3.
Joubert syndrome 4 is a type of Joubert syndrome and has an exact synonym, JBTS4. It is defined as a Joubert syndrome that has its material basis in deletions of the NPHP1 gene on chromosome 2q13.

Joubert syndrome 5 is a type of Joubert syndrome, which is defined by a Joubert syndrome that has its material basis in a mutation in the CEP290 gene on chromosome 12q21. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with JBTS5.

Joubert syndrome 6 is a type of Joubert syndrome, defined by a Joubert syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TMEM67 gene on chromosome 8q22. Additionally, Joubert syndrome 6 has the exact synonym JBTS6.

Joubert syndrome 7 is a type of Joubert syndrome that is defined as a Joubert syndrome with a material basis in mutation in the RPGRIP1L gene on chromosome 16q12.2. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with JBTS7.

Joubert Syndrome 8 is a type of Joubert Syndrome and has an exact synonym, JBTS8. It is defined as a Joubert syndrome that has its material basis in a mutation in the ARL13B gene located on chromosome 3q11.1-q11.2.

Joubert Syndrome 9 (JBTS9) is a type of Joubert Syndrome and a digenic disease, characterized by having a material basis in some form of digenic inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a Joubert Syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CC2D2A gene located on chromosome 4p15.

Cone rod dystrophy 2 is identified as a specific type of cone rod dystrophy, characterized by its definition as a cone-rod dystrophy that originates from a heterozygous mutation in the CRX gene located on chromosome 19q13. This condition is known by several exact synonyms including CORD2, CRD2, RCRD2, cone-rod retinal dystrophy 2, and retinal cone-rod dystrophy 2.

X-linked cone rod dystrophy 2 is a type of cone rod dystrophy characterized by a variation in the chromosome region Xq27. It is also exactly synonymous with COD2, CORDX2, and X-linked cone dystrophy 2.

X-linked cone rod dystrophy 3 is a type of cone rod dystrophy, which is also classified as an X-linked recessive disease. This disease is characterized by the fact that it has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. Moreover, it is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in a mutation in the CACNA1F gene on chromosome Xp11. Additionally, X-linked cone rod dystrophy 3 is exactly synonymous with CORDX3.

X-linked cone rod dystrophy 1 is a type of cone rod dystrophy with a definition that specifies it as a cone-rod dystrophy having its material basis in a mutation in an alternative terminal exon 15 of the RPGR gene on chromosome Xp11. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms COD1, CORDX1, and X-linked cone dystrophy 1.

Cone rod dystrophy 1 is a type of cone rod dystrophy and has the definition of being a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 18q21.1-q21.3. Additionally, it has the exact synonyms CORD1 and CRD1.

Cone rod dystrophy 5 is a type of cone-rod dystrophy and has an exact synonym, CORD5. It is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in a mutation in the PITPNM3 gene located in the chromosome region 17p13.2-p13.1.

Cone rod dystrophy 6 is a type of cone rod dystrophy and has a definition as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GUCY2D gene on chromosome 17p13.1. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms including CORD6, RCD2, and retinal cone dystrophy 2.
Cone rod dystrophy 7, which is a type of cone rod dystrophy, has the exact synonym CORD7. It is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 6q13.

Cone rod dystrophy 3 is a type of cone rod dystrophy, which is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ABCA4 gene on chromosome 1p22. It also has an exact synonym, CORD3.
Cone rod dystrophy 8 is a type of cone rod dystrophy and has the exact synonym CORD8. It is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 1q12-q24.

Newfoundland cone rod dystrophy is a type of cone rod dystrophy and is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RLBP1 gene on chromosome 15q26. Additionally, it has the exact synonym NFRCD.

Cone rod dystrophy 13 is a type of cone rod dystrophy and has the exact synonym CORD13. It is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in mutation in the RPGRIP1 gene on chromosome 14q11.2.

Cone rod dystrophy 10 is a type of cone-rod dystrophy and has an exact synonym, CORD10. It is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the SEMA4A gene on chromosome 1q22.

Cone rod dystrophy 11 is a type of cone rod dystrophy and has the exact synonym CORD11. It is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RAX2 gene on chromosome 19p13.

Cone rod dystrophy 12 is a type of cone rod dystrophy and is exactly synonymous with CORD12. It is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous or heterozygous mutation in the PROM1 gene on chromosome 4p15.

Cone rod dystrophy 9 is a type of cone rod dystrophy and has the exact synonym CORD9. It is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ADAM9 gene on chromosome 8p11.

Cone rod dystrophy 15 is a type of cone rod dystrophy, which is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the CDHR1 gene on chromosome 10q23. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with CORD15.

Cone rod dystrophy 16 is a type of cone rod dystrophy and has the exact synonyms CORD16 and retinal dystrophy with early macular involvement. It is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the C8ORF37 gene on chromosome 8q22.
Cone rod dystrophy 17 is a type of cone rod dystrophy and has the exact synonym CORD17. It is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 10q26.

Cone rod dystrophy 18 is a type of cone rod dystrophy, which is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the RAB28 gene on chromosome 4p15. Furthermore, it has the exact synonym CORD18.

Cone rod dystrophy 19 is a type of cone rod dystrophy, which is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TTLL5 gene on chromosome 14q24. Additionally, it has the exact synonym CORD19.

Cone rod dystrophy 20 is a type of cone rod dystrophy and has the exact synonym CORD20. It is defined as a cone-rod dystrophy that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the POC1B gene on chromosome 12q21.

Hemochromatosis type 2a is a specific type of hemochromatosis type 2 and is also known as HFE2A. It is characterized by a disease that fundamentally arises from some structural variant. Specifically, hemochromatosis type 2a is defined as a type of hemochromatosis type 2 that develops due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the HJV gene located on chromosome 1q21.

Hemochromatosis type 4 is a type of hemochromatosis and falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a hemochromatosis that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SLC40A1 gene on chromosome 2q32. This condition is exactly synonymous with HFE4, autosomal dominant hereditary hemochromatosis, ferroportin disease, and hemochromatosis due to defect in ferroportin.

Hemochromatosis type 1 is a type of hemochromatosis and also falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a hemochromatosis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the HFE gene on chromosome 6p22. Hemochromatosis type 1 is exactly synonymous with HFE1, symptomatic form of HFE-related hereditary hemochromatosis, symptomatic form of classic hemochromatosis, and symptomatic form of hemochromatosis type 1.

Hemochromatosis type 3, which is a type of hemochromatosis and falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant, is defined as a hemochromatosis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TFR2 gene on chromosome 7q22. It is also known by its exact synonyms: HFE3, TFR2-related hemochromatosis, and hemochromatosis due to a defect in transferrin receptor 2.

Hemochromatosis type 5 is a specific type of hemochromatosis that falls under the category of diseases with a basis in structural variants. It is defined as a hemochromatosis that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FTH1 gene located on chromosome 11q12. Furthermore, Hemochromatosis type 5 is exactly synonymous with FTH1-associated iron overload, FTH1-related iron overload, and HFE5.

Hemochromatosis type 2b is a specific variant of hemochromatosis type 2 and is also known as HFE2B. It is categorized under conditions that have their basis in some structural variant. Hemochromatosis type 2b is defined as a type of hemochromatosis type 2 that arises from a homozygous mutation in the HAMP gene located on chromosome 19q13.

African iron overload is a type of hemochromatosis and is defined as a hemochromatosis characterized by a predisposition to iron loading that is exacerbated by excessive intake of dietary iron, commonly related to consumption of traditional beer brewed in non-galvanized steel drums. Additionally, African iron overload has exact synonyms including Bantu siderosis and iron overload in Africa.

Hemochromatosis type 2, also known exactly as HFE2, JHH, or juvenile hemochromatosis, is a type of hemochromatosis characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance. It leads to an early onset of severe iron loading with symptoms that include hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, cardiomyopathy, arthropathy, and liver fibrosis or cirrhosis. This type of hemochromatosis is associated with several features in diseases, such as cardiomyopathy, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, arthropathy, and liver cirrhosis.

CADASIL 1 is a type of CADASIL and also a specific form of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that necessarily has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. CADASIL 1 is distinct and separate from CADASIL 2. It is defined as a CADASIL characterized by migraine, strokes, and white matter lesions, which originates from a heterozygous mutation in the NOTCH3 gene on chromosome 19p13. Additionally, CADASIL 1 is exactly synonymous with Autosomal Dominant Cerebral Arteriopathy with Subcortical Infarcts and Leukoencephalopathy Type 1.

CADASIL 2 is a type of CADASIL and an autosomal dominant disease, which is also a type of condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a CADASIL characterized by various symptoms including stroke, transient ischemic attacks, cognitive impairment, dementia, balance impairment, gait disturbance, headaches, and/or seizures. These symptoms are associated with early confluent or confluent diffuse white matter hyperintensities, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the HTRA1 gene on chromosome 10q26. Furthermore, CADASIL 2 is exactly synonymous with autosomal dominant cerebral arteriopathy with subcortical infarcts and leukoencephalopathy type 2.

Glycine N methyltransferase deficiency is a type of hypermethioninemia and is also known by its exact synonyms: GNMT deficiency, hypermethioninemia due to GNMT deficiency, and hypermethioninemia due to glycine N-methyltransferase deficiency. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of persistent isolated hypermethioninemia without cystathionine beta-synthase deficiency, tyrosinemia type I, or liver disease. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GNMT gene on chromosome 6p21.

Hypermethioninemia due to adenosine kinase deficiency is a type of hypermethioninemia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of developmental delay, early-onset seizures, mild dysmorphic features, and characteristic biochemical anomalies, including persistent hypermethioninemia. This condition has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the ADK gene on chromosome 10q22. It is exactly synonymous with ADK hypermethioninemia, MRT8, autosomal recessive mental retardation 8, hypermethioninemia encephalopathy due to ADK deficiency, and hypermethioninemia encephalopathy due to adenosine kinase deficiency.

Hypermethioninemia with deficiency of S-adenosylhomocysteine hydrolase is a type of hypermethioninemia characterized by an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern. This condition is defined by psychomotor delay, severe myopathy, hypermethioninemia, and elevated serum creatine kinase levels, which are due to a compound heterozygous mutation in the AHCY gene on chromosome 20q11. It is also known by its exact synonyms: hypermethioninemia due to S-adenosylhomocysteine hydrolase deficiency and psychomotor retardation due to S-adenosylhomocysteine hydrolase deficiency.

@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:glycogen_storage_disease_i_xd rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty :has_material_basis_in ;
            owl:someValuesFrom :x_linked_recessive_inheritance ],
        [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty :has_symptom ;
            owl:someValuesFrom :muscle_weakness ],
        :glycogen_storage_disease_ix,
        :x_linked_recessive_disease ;
    :has_definition "A glycogen storage disease IX that is characterized by X-linked inheritance of variable exercise-induced muscle weakness or stiffness that has_material_basis_in mutation in the PHKA1 gene on chromosome Xq13." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "GSD IXd"@en,
        "GSD due to muscle phosphorylase kinase deficiency"@en,
        "GSD type 9D"@en,
        "GSD type 9E"@en,
        "GSD type IXd"@en,
        "GSD type IXe"@en,
        "GSD9D"@en,
        "X-linked muscke glycogenosis"@en,
        "glycogen storage disease due to muscle phosphorylase kinase deficiency"@en,
        "glycogen storage disease type 9D"@en,
        "glycogen storage disease type 9E"@en,
        "glycogen storage disease type IXd"@en,
        "glycogen storage disease type IXe"@en,
        "glycogenosis due to muscle phosphorylase kinase deficiency"@en,
        "glycogenosis type 9D"@en,
        "glycogenosis type 9E"@en,
        "glycogenosis type IXd"@en,
        "glycogenosis type IXe"@en,
        "muscle phosphorylase kinase deficiency"@en .
text:
Glycogen storage disease IXd is a type of glycogen storage disease IX and is also classified as an X-linked recessive disease. It shares a characteristic of having a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance and presents with at least one symptom, notably muscle weakness. Glycogen storage disease IXd is specifically defined as a glycogen storage disease IX characterized by X-linked inheritance of variable exercise-induced muscle weakness or stiffness, which is caused by a mutation in the PHKA1 gene on chromosome Xq13.

Furthermore, Glycogen storage disease IXd is known by an array of exact synonyms including GSD IXd, GSD due to muscle phosphorylase kinase deficiency, GSD type 9D, GSD type 9E, GSD type IXd, GSD type IXe, GSD9D, X-linked muscle glycogenosis, glycogen storage disease due to muscle phosphorylase kinase deficiency, glycogen storage disease type 9D, glycogen storage disease type 9E, glycogen storage disease type IXd, glycogen storage disease type IXe, glycogenosis due to muscle phosphorylase kinase deficiency, glycogenosis type 9D, glycogenosis type 9E, glycogenosis type IXd, glycogenosis type IXe, and muscle phosphorylase kinase deficiency.

Glycogen storage disease IXb (GSD IXb) is a type of glycogen storage disease IX, characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of hepatomegaly, short stature, hypotonia, and accumulation of glycogen in both liver and muscle, without clinical symptoms. This condition has its basis in a compound heterozygous mutation in the PHKB gene on chromosome 16q12. It is associated with symptoms such as hepatomegaly, left upper quadrant abdominal rigidity, and short stature, and its disease basis involves some structural variant. GSD IXb is also known by several exact synonyms, including GSD IXb, GSD due to liver and muscle phosphorylase kinase deficiency, GSD type 9B, GSD type IXb, GSD9B, glycogen storage disease type 9B, glycogen storage disease type IXb, glycogenosis due to liver and muscle phosphorylase kinase deficiency, glycogenosis type 9B, and glycogenosis type IXb.

Glycogen Storage Disease I Xa (GSD IXa) is a type of Glycogen Storage Disease IX and is also categorized as an X-linked recessive disease. This classification is due to its material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. GSD IXa exhibits symptoms including hepatomegaly and left upper quadrant abdominal rigidity. It is characterized by a variety of manifestations such as hepatomegaly, growth retardation, elevation of glutamate-pyruvate transaminase and glutamate-oxaloacetate transaminase, hypercholesterolemia, hypertriglyceridemia, and fasting hyperketosis. However, these symptoms tend to gradually disappear with age. The disease is specifically associated with a mutation in the PHKA2 gene on chromosome Xp22.

GSD IXa is known by several exact synonyms, including GSD Type 9A, GSD Type IXa, GSD9A, Glycogen Storage Disease Type 9A, Glycogen Storage Disease Type IXa, Glycogenosis Type 9A, and Glycogenosis Type IXa.

Glycogen storage disease IXc, also known as GSD type 9C, GSD type IXc, GSD9C, glycogen storage disease type 9C, glycogen storage disease type IXc, glycogenosis type 9C, and glycogenosis type IXc, is a specific form of glycogen storage disease IX and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with symptoms such as hepatomegaly and left upper quadrant abdominal rigidity. This disease has a material basis in homozygous and compound heterozygous mutations in the PHKG2 gene on chromosome 16p11. It is defined as a glycogen storage disease IX characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of hepatomegaly, hypotonia, growth retardation, liver dysfunction with onset in childhood, and improvement of symptoms with age.

Gray Platelet Syndrome (GPS) is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal recessive disease, a blood platelet disease, and it is characterized by a basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It also has symptoms that include bleeding. Specifically, GPS is defined as a blood platelet disease characterized by a selective deficiency in the number and contents of platelet alpha-granules, macrothrombocytopenia, enlarged platelets, myelofibrosis, splenomegaly, and an increased bleeding time. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NBEAL2 gene on chromosome 3p21. Furthermore, Gray Platelet Syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms including BDPLT4, GPS, platelet alpha-granule deficiency, and platelet-type bleeding disorder 4.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 9 (BDPLT9), which is also known as GP Ia deficiency, collagen platelet receptor deficiency, and glycoprotein Ia deficiency, is recognized as a type of autosomal dominant disease. Specifically, it falls under the category of blood platelet diseases that manifest due to autosomal dominant inheritance, which includes mild thrombocytopenia, mild alpha-granule deficiency, and defective platelet adhesion. The disorder's material basis is found in a mutation in the ITGA2 gene located on chromosome 5q11.2.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 10, also known exactly as BDPLT10, CD36 deficiency, and platelet glycoprotein IV deficiency, is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease, a type of blood platelet disease that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by symptoms such as bleeding and is defined as a blood platelet disease marked by an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern. This disorder involves variable bleeding tendencies, thrombocytopenia, the presence of giant platelets, and prolonged bleeding times, which are attributed to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CD36 antigen gene located on chromosome 7q21.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 14, also known exactly as BDPLT14 or thromboxane synthase deficiency, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that falls under the category of blood platelet diseases. This disorder is characterized by specific symptoms including bleeding, and it is defined by a defective platelet aggregation leading to conditions such as epistaxis, ecchymoses, and prolonged bleeding times. The material basis for this disorder is a mutation in the TBXAS1 gene located on chromosome 7q34, indicating an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 19 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, blood platelet disease, and it is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a blood platelet disease characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of symptoms such as epistaxis, spontaneous hematomas, severe thrombocytopenia, menorrhagia, ovarian cyst ruptures, and abnormal megakaryocytic clusters, which is caused by a homozygous mutation in the PRKACG gene on chromosome 9q21. Furthermore, platelet type bleeding disorder 19 has exact synonyms, including BDPLT19 and severe autosomal recessive macrothrombocytopenia.

Platelet Type Bleeding Disorder 17 (BDPLT17), also known as hereditary thrombasthenia-thrombocytopenia, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific kind of blood platelet disease. This condition is characterized by an increased bleeding tendency, gray platelets, thrombocytopenia, thrombasthenia, abnormal megakaryocytes, decreased or absent alpha-granules in platelets, and myelofibrosis. It is noted for having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and symptoms that include bleeding. The disorder is defined by a heterozygous mutation in the GFI1B gene on chromosome 9q34.

Quebec platelet disorder is a type of blood platelet disease that also falls under the category of conditions that present with symptoms such as bleeding. It is defined as a blood platelet disease characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance featuring delayed onset bleeding after challenge, moderate to severe bleeding tendencies, frequent ecchymoses, mucocutaneous bleeding, muscle and joint bleeds, and platelet alpha-granule degradation. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous tandem duplication of the PLAU gene located on chromosome 10q22. Additionally, Quebec platelet disorder is known by several exact synonyms, including BDPLT5, factor V Quebec, and platelet-type bleeding disorder 5.

Platelet Type Bleeding Disorder 18 (BDPLT18), also known as a bleeding disorder due to CalDAG-GEFI deficiency or due to calcium- and DAG-regulated guanine exchange factor-1 deficiency, is a specific type of blood platelet disease. This condition is characterized by being an autosomal recessive disease, which at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and has symptoms including bleeding. Specifically, it is described as a blood platelet disease characterized by mucocutaneous bleeding, prolonged and severe epistaxis, hematomas, and bleeding after tooth extraction. This condition results from a homozygous mutation in the RASGRP2 gene located on chromosome 11q13.

Scott syndrome is a type of blood coagulation disease characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of hemorrhagic episodes due to impaired platelet coagulant activity. This disease has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the TMEM16F gene on chromosome 12q12. It has several exact synonyms, including BDPLT7, SCTS, bleeding abnormality due to deficiency of platelet binding of factor X, familial prothrombin consumption inhibitor, familial prothrombin conversion defect, platelet-type bleeding disorder 7, and prothrombin consumption deficiency.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 15 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of blood platelet disease that has at least a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and symptoms that include bleeding. It is defined as a blood platelet disease characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of macrothrombocytopenia with little or no bleeding tendency and normal in vitro platelet function, which has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ACTN1 gene on chromosome 14q. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms, including BDPLT15 and autosomal dominant macrothrombocytopenia ACTN1-related.

Von Willebrand's disease 3 is a type of Von Willebrand's disease and is also characterized as a type of condition that at least has the symptom of some bleeding. It is defined as a Von Willebrand's disease characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of a severe quantitative defect or virtual absence of VWF in plasma, prolonged bleeding time, and more severe bleeding tendencies compared to the other types of Von Willebrand disease. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the VWF gene, which maps to chromosome 12p13. Moreover, Von Willebrand's disease 3 has exact synonyms: VWD type 3, VWD3, von Willebrand disease type 3, and von Willebrand disease type III.

Platelet Type Bleeding Disorder 20, also known exactly as BDPLT20 or autosomal dominant thrombocytopenia with platelet secretion defect, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, blood platelet disease, and something that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is characterized by symptoms including bleeding. It is defined as a blood platelet disease characterized by an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern that leads to an increased bleeding tendency, thrombocytopenia, decreased platelet dense granules and ATP secretion, and impaired megakaryocyte maturation. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SLFN14 gene on chromosome 17q12.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is a subgroup of blood platelet diseases. It specifically involves a condition that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The disorder is characterized by an enhanced binding of von Willebrand factor by the platelet glycoprotein Ib receptor complex, due to a mutation in the GP1BA gene located on chromosome 17p13.2. Furthermore, Platelet type bleeding disorder 3 is also known by several exact synonyms: BDPLT3, PT-VWD, platelet type-von Willebrand disease, pseudo-von Willebrand disease, and von Willebrand disease platelet-type.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 11 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of blood platelet disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and at least has the symptom of some bleeding. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of mild to moderate bleeding and defective platelet activation and aggregation in response to collagen, with a material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the GP6 gene on chromosome 19q13. Platelet type bleeding disorder 11 has exact synonyms BDPLT11, GP VI deficiency, and glycoprotein VI deficiency.

Platelet type bleeding disorder 12 is a specific type of blood platelet disease that is classified as an autosomal dominant disease. This condition is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and commonly presents with symptoms such as increased bleeding. It specifically involves a platelet aggregation defect and an impaired conversion of arachidonic acid to thromboxane A2 in platelets, attributed to a deficiency in PTGS1 activity. Platelet type bleeding disorder 12 is also known by several exact synonyms including BDPLT12, PGHS1 deficiency, platelet COX1 deficiency, platelet cyclooxygenase 1 deficiency, and platelet prostaglandin-endoperoxide synthase 1 deficiency.

Bernard Soulier Syndrome Type A2 is a specific form of Bernard Soulier Syndrome that is characterized by an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern leading to a mild to moderate tendency to bleed, thrombocytopenia, and an increased mean platelet size. This condition arises due to heterozygous mutations in the GP1BA gene located on chromosome 17p. Moreover, it is also classified as a type of condition that includes bleeding as at least one of its symptoms. Additionally, Bernard Soulier Syndrome Type A2 is exactly synonymous with BSSA2.

Ambras type hypertrichosis universalis congenita is a type of hypertrichosis that is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of the presence of vellus-type hair covering the entire body, especially notable on the face, ears, and shoulders, but excluding the palms, soles, and mucous membranes. This condition is caused by chromosomal abnormalities in the region 8q22. It is also exactly synonymous with Ambras syndrome and HTC1.

Familial hypobetalipoproteinemia 2 (FHBL2), also known as combined familial hypolipidemia, is a type of hypobetalipoproteinemia. It is distinct from familial hypobetalipoproteinemia 1, indicating that these two conditions do not overlap. FHBL2 is characterized by having a material basis in either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ANGPTL3 gene located on chromosome 1p31.
Familial hypobetalipoproteinemia 1 is a type of hypobetalipoproteinemia that has a material basis in mutation in the APOB gene on chromosome 2p24. It is also exactly synonymous with FHBL1.

@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .

:hyperphosphatemic_familial_tumoral_calcinosis rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty :has_material_basis_in ;
            owl:someValuesFrom :autosomal_recessive_inheritance ],
        :autosomal_recessive_disease,
        :calcinosis,
        :inherited_metabolic_disorder ;
    :has_definition "A calcinosis characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of elevated blood calcium levels and calcium phosphate crystals in cutaneous and subcutaneous tissues that has_material_basis_in mutation in the GALNT3 gene, the FGF23 gene, or the KL gene." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "HFTC"@en,
        "HHS"@en,
        "PHPTC"@en,
        "cortical hyperostosis with hyperphosphatemia"@en,
        "familial Teutschlaender disease"@en,
        "familial hyperphosphatemic tumoral calcinosis/hyperphosphatemic hyperostosis syndrome"@en,
        "hypercalcemic tumoral calcinosis"@en,
        "hyperostosis with hyperphosphatemia"@en,
        "hyperphosphatemia hyperostosis"@en,
        "hyperphosphatemia hyperostosis syndrome"@en,
        "hyperphosphatemia tumoral calcinosis"@en,
        "lipocalcinogranulomatosis"@en,
        "morbus Teutschlaender"@en,
        "primary hyperphosphatemic tumoral calcinosis"@en,
        "tumoral calcinosis with hyperphosphatemia"@en .
text: Hyperphosphatemic familial tumoral calcinosis is a type of autosomal recessive disease, inherited metabolic disorder, and calcinosis, which essentially has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a calcinosis characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of elevated blood calcium levels and calcium phosphate crystals in cutaneous and subcutaneous tissues, which originates from mutations in the GALNT3, FGF23, or KL genes. This condition is known by several exact synonyms including HFTC, HHS, PHPTC, cortical hyperostosis with hyperphosphatemia, familial Teutschlaender disease, familial hyperphosphatemic tumoral calcinosis/hyperphosphatemic hyperostosis syndrome, hypercalcemic tumoral calcinosis, hyperostosis with hyperphosphatemia, hyperphosphatemia hyperostosis, hyperphosphatemia hyperostosis syndrome, hyperphosphatemia tumoral calcinosis, lipocalcinogranulomatosis, morbus Teutschlaender, primary hyperphosphatemic tumoral calcinosis, and tumoral calcinosis with hyperphosphatemia.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 1 is a type of autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy and also a type of condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific spinal muscular atrophy is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of severe respiratory distress resulting from diaphragmatic paralysis, predominantly involving the upper limbs and distal muscles. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IGHMBP2 gene on chromosome 11q13. Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 1 is precisely referred to by several exact synonyms: DSMA1, SIANRF, SMARD1, autosomal recessive distal spinal muscular atrophy 1, autosomal recessive spinal muscular atrophy with respiratory distress, dHMN6, diaphragmatic spinal muscular atrophy, distal hereditary motor neuropathy type 6, distal spinal muscular atrophy 1, distal-HMN type 6, severe infantile axonal neuropathy with respiratory failure type 1, and spinal muscular atrophy with respiratory distress type 1.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 2 (DSMA2) is a type of autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy. It is characterized by a spinal muscular atrophy that presents with autosomal recessive inheritance of distal muscle weakness and muscle wasting, primarily affecting the upper and lower limbs, typically beginning in the first decade of life. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the SIGMAR1 gene located on chromosome 9p13. DSMA2 is associated with symptoms such as muscle weakness and is understood to involve autosomal recessive inheritance. It also goes by several exact synonyms, including autosomal recessive distal spinal muscular atrophy 2, dHMNJ, distal hereditary motor neuropathy Jerash type, distal spinal muscular atrophy 2, and spinal muscular atrophy Jerash type.

Congenital bile acid synthesis defect 5 is a type of congenital bile acid synthesis defect that is characterized by hepatomegaly, liver fibrosis and failure, splenomegaly, and elevated plasma levels of bile acid intermediates. This condition is caused by homozygous mutation in the ABCD3 gene on chromosome 1p21. It is also known by its exact synonym, CBAS5. This condition manifests with symptoms such as left upper quadrant abdominal rigidity and has its basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth as well as structural variants.

Congenital bile acid synthesis defect 6 (CBAS6) is a type of congenital bile acid synthesis defect and is categorized under diseases that originate from abnormalities of prenatal development or birth as well as from structural variants. It is defined as a congenital bile acid synthesis defect characterized by symptoms such as increased liver enzymes, decreased cholesterol, and elevated serum and urine levels of bile acid intermediates, which results from a homozygous mutation in the ACOX2 gene located on chromosome 3p14.

Congenital bile acid synthesis defect 4 is a type of congenital bile acid synthesis defect and also falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth as well as structural variants. It is characterized by intrahepatic cholestasis, malabsorption of fat and fat-soluble vitamins, decreased serum cholesterol, and increased levels of THCA in bile, serum, and urine, due to a homozygous mutation in the AMACR gene on chromosome 5p13. This condition is exactly synonymous with CBAS4, intrahepatic cholestasis with defective conversion of trihydroxycoprostanic acid to cholic acid, and the presence of trihydroxycoprostanic acid in bile.

Congenital bile acid synthesis defect 2 (CBAS2), also known as cholestasis with delta(4)-3-oxosteroid 5-beta-reductase deficiency, is a subtype of congenital bile acid synthesis defect. It is characterized by the rapid progression of severe cholestatic liver disease, decreased levels of chenodeoxycholic acid and cholic acid in the serum and urine, and malabsorption of fat and fat-soluble vitamins, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the AKR1D1 gene on chromosome 7q33. This condition is categorized under diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth and also fall under diseases that are based on structural variants.

Congenital bile acid synthesis defect 3 is a type of congenital bile acid synthesis defect that falls under the category of diseases with a basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth and structural variants. This condition is characterized by intrahepatic cholestasis, malabsorption of fat and fat-soluble vitamins, and increased serum bilirubin, which is due to a homozygous mutation in the CYP7B1 gene located on chromosome 8q12. Additionally, congenital bile acid synthesis defect 3 is precisely known as CBAS3 and oxysterol 7-alpha-hydroxylase deficiency.

Congenital bile acid synthesis defect 1 (CBAS1) is a type of congenital bile acid synthesis defect, which is categorized based on its origins in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth and structural variants. It is characterized by a progression of cholestatic liver disease, giant cell hepatitis, malabsorption of fat and fat-soluble vitamins, alongside increased serum bilirubin and decreased serum cholesterol. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the HSD3B7 gene located on chromosome 16p.

Myostatin related muscle hypertrophy is a type of muscle tissue disease characterized by increased muscle bulk and strength, which has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the MSTN gene on chromosome 2q32.2. This condition also has the exact synonym MSLHP.

Progressive familial heart block is a type of heart conduction disease characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of a cardiac conduction defect that may progress to complete atrioventricular (AV) block. It may be asymptomatic or manifest as shortness of breath, dizziness, syncope, abdominal pain, heart failure, or sudden death. This condition has several symptoms including heart failure, syncope, abdominal pain, dizziness, and dyspnea. Progressive familial heart block is also known by several exact synonyms: PFHB, familial Lenegre disease, familial Lev disease, familial Lev-Lenegre disease, familial PCCD, familial progressive heart block, and hereditary bundle branch defect.

Progressive Familial Heart Block Type IA (PFHB1A) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically a variant of Progressive Familial Heart Block, characterized by a cardiac bundle branch disorder that may progress to complete heart block. This condition fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance and has its material basis in a mutation in the SCN5A gene located on chromosome 3p21.

Progressive Familial Heart Block Type II (PFHB2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the broader category of progressive familial heart blocks. This condition has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance and is characterized by symptoms such as sinus bradycardia. Specifically, it is defined as a progressive familial heart block that exhibits autosomal dominant inheritance patterns of heart block, which often progresses in the manner of sinus bradycardia with a left posterior hemiblock. This condition can present clinically through syncopal episodes, Stokes-Adams seizures, or even sudden death when complete heart block occurs, due to variations in the chromosome region 1q32.

Progressive Familial Heart Block Type IB is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also a specific variety of Progressive Familial Heart Block. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as a progressive familial heart block characterized by a heterozygous mutation in the TRPM4 gene on chromosome 19q13. Additionally, Progressive Familial Heart Block Type IB is exactly synonymous with PFHB1B.

Pyruvate kinase deficiency of red cells, also exactly known as PK deficiency, hemolytic anemia due to red cell pyruvate kinase deficiency, and pyruvate kinase deficiency of erythrocyte, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, congenital nonspherocytic hemolytic anemia, and a condition with a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a congenital nonspherocytic hemolytic anemia that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PKLR gene on chromosome 1q22.

Tibial muscular dystrophy is a type of autosomal dominant disease, distal myopathy, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a distal myopathy characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of late-onset muscular dystrophy beginning in the anterior compartment of the legs, having a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding the giant skeletal muscle protein titin (TTN) on chromosome 2q31. Tibial muscular dystrophy is also known by several exact synonyms, including Finnish tibial muscular dystrophy, TMD, Tardive tibial muscular dystrophy, Udd myopathy, Udd type distal myopathy, and distal titinopathy.

Birdshot chorioretinopathy is a type of posterior uveitis and is defined as a posterior uveitis characterized by multiple small, hypopigmented, cream-colored choroidal lesions scattered symmetrically in the fundus primarily around the optic disc. It presents in patients as blurred vision, floaters, photopsia, scotoma, and nyctalopia. Birdshot chorioretinopathy has exact synonyms including BSCR, birdshot chorioretinitis, birdshot retinochoroiditis, birdshot retinochoroidopathy, and vitiliginous choroiditis.

Fanconi anemia complementation group V (FANCV) is identified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a variation of Fanconi anemia. It is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Importantly, FANCV is defined by a Fanconi anemia that originates from a homozygous mutation in the MAD2L2 gene located on chromosome 1p36.

Fanconi anemia complementation group T, which has the exact synonym FANCT, is a type of Fanconi anemia and a specific autosomal recessive disease. It belongs to a category of disorders that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This particular Fanconi anemia is defined by a compound heterozygous mutation in the UBE2T gene located on chromosome 1q32.

Fanconi anemia complementation group L (FANCL) is a type of Fanconi anemia and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this form of Fanconi anemia is defined by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PHF9 gene located on chromosome 2p16.

Fanconi anemia complementation group D2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is a specific form of Fanconi anemia. This disease is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a Fanconi anemia that results from either compound heterozygous or homozygous mutations in the FANCD2 gene located on chromosome 3p25. Furthermore, Fanconi anemia complementation group D2 is also known by several exact synonyms, including FA4, FAD2, FANCD2, and Fanconi pancytopenia type 4.

Fanconi Anemia Complementation Group E (FACE) is a type of Fanconi Anemia and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this type of Fanconi Anemia, also known by its exact synonym FANCE, is defined by a homozygous mutation in the FANCE gene located on chromosome 6p22-p21.

Fanconi anemia complementation group U, also known exactly as FANCU, is a type of autosomal recessive disease as well as a subtype of Fanconi anemia. It is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined by a Fanconi anemia that arises from a homozygous mutation in the XRCC2 gene located on chromosome 7q36.

Fanconi anemia complementation group G, which is also known exactly as FANCG, is identified as a type of monogenic disease and a specific variation of Fanconi anemia. This categorization implies it is part of the broader spectrum of diseases that have their basis in genetic mutations. Specifically, it is defined as a Fanconi anemia that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the XRCC9 gene located on chromosome 9p13.

Fanconi anemia complementation group C, which is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also categorized under Fanconi anemia, is defined as a Fanconi anemia that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FANCC gene on chromosome 9q22. It is characterized by something that at least has its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is precisely known by its exact synonyms FA3, FACC, FANCC, and Fanconi pancytopenia type 3.

Fanconi anemia complementation group F is a type of monogenic disease, Fanconi anemia, and something that at least one disease has a basis in some gene. It is defined as a Fanconi anemia that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FANCF gene on chromosome 11p15. Furthermore, it has an exact synonym, FANCF.

Fanconi anemia complementation group D1 is a type of Fanconi anemia and a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is a subset of diseases that at least have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a Fanconi anemia that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the BRCA2 gene on chromosome 13q13. Additionally, Fanconi anemia complementation group D1 is exactly synonymized with FAD1 and FANCD1.

Fanconi anemia complementation group R, which is exactly synonymous with FANCR, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of Fanconi anemia. This particular disease is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a Fanconi anemia that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RAD51 gene located on chromosome 15q15.

Fanconi anemia complementation group I is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of Fanconi anemia, which is characterized by conditions that at least have a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a Fanconi anemia that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FANCI gene on chromosome 15q26. Moreover, it has the exact synonym FANCI.

Fanconi anemia complementation group P, which has the exact synonym FANCP, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, and specifically, a type of Fanconi anemia. It is defined as a Fanconi anemia characterized by increased chromosomal instability, progressive bone marrow failure, and in some cases, skeletal abnormalities. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLX4 gene on chromosome 16p13.3. Furthermore, it is a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Fanconi anemia complementation group Q (FANCQ) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the category of Fanconi anemia. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a Fanconi anemia that has a material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the ERCC4 gene on chromosome 16p13.

Fanconi anemia complementation group N is a type of monogenic disease and a type of Fanconi anemia, characterized by a basis in genetic origins. Specifically, it is defined as a Fanconi anemia that has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the PALB2 gene on chromosome 16p12. Additionally, it has the exact synonym FANCN.

Fanconi anemia complementation group A (FANCA) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of Fanconi anemia. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. FANCA is defined as a Fanconi anemia that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the FANCA gene located on chromosome 16q24. Additionally, FANCA is exactly synonymous with Fanconi anemia complementation group A.

Fanconi anemia complementation group O, which has the exact synonym FANCO, is a type of Fanconi anemia and a specific kind of autosomal recessive disease. This condition can be broadly categorized as something that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a Fanconi anemia that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the RAD51C gene located on chromosome 17q21-q24.

Fanconi anemia complementation group J (FANCJ) is a type of monogenic disease and a type of Fanconi anemia, which is a category of diseases that have a basis in genetic mutations. Specifically, this condition is defined as a Fanconi anemia that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the BRIP1 gene located on chromosome 17q22. Additionally, Fanconi anemia complementation group J is also known by its exact synonym, FANCJ.

Fanconi anemia complementation group B, which has the exact synonyms FACB, FANCB, and Fanconi pancytopenia type 2, is a type of Fanconi anemia and a form of X-linked recessive disease. It specifically has a material basis in a mutation in the FANCB gene located on chromosome Xp22, which classifies it as a condition that at least partially arises from X-linked recessive inheritance.

Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young Type 1 (MODY1) is a type of Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young, which falls under the category of diseases that have a basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a maturity-onset diabetes of the young that has its material basis in a mutation in the HNF4A gene on chromosome 20. Moreover, it is also known by several exact synonyms including Diabetes Mellitus Type 2, MODY type 1, MODY1, and mild juvenile diabetes mellitus.

Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young Type 2 is a specific type of Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young and also falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a maturity-onset diabetes of the young that has its material basis in heterozygous mutation in the GCK gene on chromosome 7p13. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with MODY glucokinase-related, MODY type 2, and MODY2.

Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young Type 5 (MODY5) is a subtype of Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young. It is characterized as a type of condition that, like other diseases, has its basis in some structural variant. Specifically, MODY5 is defined as a form of maturity-onset diabetes of the young characterized by abnormal renal development resulting in non-diabetic kidney disease and diabetes, which is caused by a mutation in the HNF1B gene on chromosome 17q12. MODY5 is also known by several exact synonyms, including CAKUT with diabetes, MODY5, RCAD, atypical FJHN, atypical familial juvenile hyperuricemic nephropathy, congenital anomalies of the kidney and urinary tract with diabetes, familial hypoplastic glomerulocystic kidney, hypoplastic type glomerulocystic kidney disease, and renal cysts and diabetes syndrome.

Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young Type 3 (MODY3) is a type of Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young, which is part of a broader category defined by diseases having their basis in some structural variant. Specifically, MODY3 is defined as a maturity-onset diabetes of the young that has its material basis in a mutation in the HNF1A gene located on chromosome 12q24.31. Furthermore, Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young Type 3 is exactly synonymous with MODY type 3 and MODY3.

Maturity onset diabetes of the young type 4 (MODY type 4 or MODY4) is a specific type of maturity onset diabetes of the young. This disease is characterized by its basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a maturity-onset diabetes of the young that has its material basis in a mutation in the PDX1 gene located on chromosome 13q12.2.

Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young Type 6 (MODY6) is a specific type of Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young, which is also known by its exact synonyms, MODY Type 6 and MODY6. It is characterized by a form of the disease that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NEUROD1 gene located on chromosome 2q31. This condition falls under the broader category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant.

Maturity onset diabetes of the young type 8 is a specific type of maturity onset diabetes of the young, defined by a material basis in frameshift deletions in the variable number of tandem repeats of the CEL gene on chromosome 9q34.13. This condition is exactly synonymous with MODY type 8, MODY8, diabetes and pancreatic exocrine dysfunction, and maturity-onset diabetes of the young type 8 with exocrine dysfunction.

Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young Type 7 (MODY7) is a specific type of Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young. It is characterized by having a basis in some structural variant, indicating that at least one disease falls into this category. The definition of MODY7 is a Maturity-Onset Diabetes of the Young that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KLF11 gene located on chromosome 2p25. Furthermore, MODY7 is exactly synonymous with MODY7, emphasizing its specific classification within the broader category of Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young.

Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young Type 9 (MODY9) is a specific type of Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young. It is also a type of condition that, like at least one other disease, has its basis in some structural variant. Importantly, MODY9 is defined as a maturity-onset diabetes of the young that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PAX4 gene located on chromosome 7q32.1.
