Maturity onset diabetes of the young type 10 (MODY10) is a subtype of maturity onset diabetes of the young. It is characterized by a specific structure, being a type of condition that has its basis in some structural variant. The definition of MODY10 is a maturity-onset diabetes of the young that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the INS gene located on chromosome 11p15.5.

Maturity onset diabetes of the young type 11 is a type of maturity onset diabetes of the young and is also a type of condition that has its basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a maturity-onset diabetes of the young that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BLK gene on chromosome 8p23-p22. Additionally, maturity onset diabetes of the young type 11 has an exact synonym, MODY11.

Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young Type 13 is a type of Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young and is also a type of condition that has its basis in some structural variant. This specific diabetes type is defined as a maturity-onset diabetes of the young that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KCNJ11 gene located on chromosome 11p15. Additionally, Maturity Onset Diabetes of the Young Type 13 has exact synonyms, which include MODY type 13 and MODY13.

Maturity onset diabetes of the young type 14 is a specific type of maturity onset diabetes of the young and is also a type of condition that has its basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a maturity-onset diabetes of the young that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the APPL1 gene on chromosome 3p14. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with MODY14.

Nephronophthisis 1 is a type of nephronophthisis with a definition as a nephronophthisis that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in or deletion of the NPHP1 gene on chromosome 2q13. It has exact synonyms NPH1, NPHP1, and juvenile nephronophthisis 1.

Nephronophthisis 2 is a type of nephronophthisis characterized by a condition that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the INVS gene on chromosome 9q31. It is exactly synonymous with NPH2, NPHP2, and infantile nephronophthisis 2.

Nephronophthisis 3 is a type of nephronophthisis, which is defined as a nephronophthisis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NPHP3 gene on chromosome 3q22. Moreover, it has exact synonyms NPH3 and NPHP3.

Nephronophthisis 4 is a type of nephronophthisis that has a material basis in mutation in the NPHP4 gene located on chromosome 1p36.31. It is exactly synonymous with NPHP4 and juvenile nephronophthisis 4.

Nephronophthisis 7 is a type of nephronophthisis and it is exactly synonymous with NPHP7. It is defined as a nephronophthisis that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the GLIS2 gene on chromosome 16p13.

Nephronophthisis like nephropathy 1 is a type of nephronophthisis and it is also known exactly as NPHPL1. This particular nephronophthisis is defined by having a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the XPNPEP3 gene located on chromosome 22q13.2.

Nephronophthisis 11 is a type of nephronophthisis and has an exact synonym NPHP11. It is defined as a nephronophthisis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TMEM67 gene on chromosome 8q22.1.

Nephronophthisis 12 is a type of nephronophthisis and it is exactly synonymous with NPHP12. It is defined as a nephronophthisis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TTC21B gene on chromosome 2q24.

Nephronophthisis 9 is a type of nephronophthisis and has the exact synonym NPHP9. It is defined as a nephronophthisis that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the NEK8 gene on chromosome 17q11.

Nephronophthisis 13 is a type of nephronophthisis, which is defined as a nephronophthisis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the WDR19 gene on chromosome 4p14. Additionally, it has the exact synonym NPHP13.

Nephronophthisis 14 is a type of nephronophthisis and has an exact synonym, NPHP14. It is defined as a nephronophthisis that has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the ZNF423 gene on chromosome 16q12.1.

Nephronophthisis 15 is a type of nephronophthisis and is exactly synonymous with NPHP15. It is defined as a nephronophthisis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CEP164 gene on chromosome 11q.

Nephronophthisis 16 is a type of nephronophthisis and it is exactly synonymous with NPHP16. It is defined as a nephronophthisis that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the ANKS6 gene on chromosome 9q22.

Nephronophthisis 18 is a type of nephronophthisis and has an exact synonym, NPHP18. It is defined as a nephronophthisis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CEP83 gene on chromosome 12q22.

Nephronophthisis 19 is a type of nephronophthisis and has an exact synonym, NPHP19. It is defined as a nephronophthisis that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DCDC2 gene on chromosome 6p22.

Nephronophthisis 20 is a type of nephronophthisis, which is defined as a nephronophthisis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MAPKBP1 gene on chromosome 15q15. Furthermore, Nephronophthisis 20 is exactly synonymous with NPHP20.

Focal Segmental Glomerulosclerosis 1 (FSGS1) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a specific type of Focal Segmental Glomerulosclerosis. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, FSGS1 is defined as a focal segmental glomerulosclerosis that results from an autosomal dominant mutation of the ACTN4 gene located on chromosome 19q13.2.

Focal Segmental Glomerulosclerosis 2 (FSGS2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also falls under the broader category of focal segmental glomerulosclerosis. It is characterized by a specific type that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of FSGS2 is a focal segmental glomerulosclerosis that is caused by a mutation of the TRPC6 gene located on chromosome 11q22.1. Additionally, FSGS2 is exactly synonymous with the term FSGS2, indicating its specific identification within the realm of medical conditions.

Focal Segmental Glomerulosclerosis 5 (FSGS5) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of focal segmental glomerulosclerosis. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as a focal segmental glomerulosclerosis that arises from an autosomal dominant mutation of the INF2 gene located on chromosome 14q32.33.

Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis 6 (FSGS6) is a type of focal segmental glomerulosclerosis and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a specific type that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. FSGS6 is defined as a focal segmental glomerulosclerosis that has its material basis in an autosomal recessive mutation of the MYO1E gene on chromosome 15q22.2.

Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis 7 (FSGS7) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a variant of focal segmental glomerulosclerosis. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically through an autosomal dominant mutation of the PAX2 gene located on chromosome 10q24.31.

Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis 8 (FSGS8) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of focal segmental glomerulosclerosis. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, FSGS8 is defined as a focal segmental glomerulosclerosis that arises due to an autosomal dominant mutation of the ANLN gene located on chromosome 7p14.2.

Focal Segmental Glomerulosclerosis 9 (FSGS9) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of focal segmental glomerulosclerosis. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, particularly defined as a focal segmental glomerulosclerosis that has its material basis in an autosomal recessive mutation of the CRB2 gene on chromosome 9q33.3.

Congenital generalized lipodystrophy type 1 is a type of congenital generalized lipodystrophy and also falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital generalized lipodystrophy characterized by having a material basis in an autosomal recessive mutation of AGPAT2 on chromosome 9q34.3. Furthermore, congenital generalized lipodystrophy type 1 is exactly synonymous with Berardinelli-Seip Congenital Lipodystrophy, Type 1, and Brunzell syndrome AGPAT2-related.

Congenital Generalized Lipodystrophy Type 2 (CGL2) is a type of congenital generalized lipodystrophy, which falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined by a congenital generalized lipodystrophy that arises due to an autosomal recessive mutation of the BSCL2 gene located on chromosome 11q12.3. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms, including Berardinelli-Seip Congenital Lipodystrophy Type 2, Berardinelli-Seip Syndrome, Brunzell Syndrome BSCL2-related, Congenital Lipoatrophic Diabetes, and Total Lipodystrophy and Acromegaloid Gigantism.

Congenital Generalized Lipodystrophy Type 3 is a type of congenital generalized lipodystrophy and also falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital generalized lipodystrophy that results from an autosomal recessive mutation of CAV1 on chromosome 7q31.2. Additionally, this condition is exactly synonymous with Berardinelli-Seip congenital lipodystrophy type 3.

Congenital Generalized Lipodystrophy Type 4 is a specific type of Congenital Generalized Lipodystrophy. It falls under the broader category of diseases that originate from abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. This condition is defined by a congenital generalized lipodystrophy that results from an autosomal recessive mutation of the CAVIN1 gene located on chromosome 17q21.2. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including Berardinelli-Seip Congenital Lipodystrophy Type 4 with Muscular Dystrophy, Congenital Generalised Lipodystrophy Type 4, Generalised Congenital Lipodystrophy Type 4, Generalised Congenital Lipodystrophy with Myopathy, Generalized Congenital Lipodystrophy Type 4, and Generalized Congenital Lipodystrophy with Myopathy.

Mitochondrial Complex III deficiency, which is a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease, is defined as a condition characterized by the impaired function of one or more of the proteins making up the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex III.

IGSF1 deficiency syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. This syndrome is specifically characterized by hypothyroidism present at birth, a delayed increase in testosterone during puberty, and testicular enlargement in adulthood, which is due to a mutation of the IGSF1 gene located on chromosome Xq26. Furthermore, IGSF1 deficiency syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including CHTE, X-linked central congenital hypothyroidism with late-onset macroorchidism, X-linked central congenital hypothyroidism with late-onset testicular enlargement, and central hypothyroidism and testicular enlargement. This condition is a manifestation of a type of syndrome that inherently has a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance.
Delayed Sleep Phase Syndrome (DSPD) is a type of sleep disorder characterized by an extreme evening preference, sleep-onset insomnia, and difficulty in awakening at the desired time.

Oligomeganephronia is a type of renal hypoplasia and has the definition of being a renal hypoplasia characterized by bilateral reduced kidney size with a marked decrease in the total number of nephrons. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, which is Oligomeganephronic renal hypoplasia.

Mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency is a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease characterized by impaired function of one or more of the proteins making up the mitochondrial proton-transporting ATP synthase complex.

Preterm premature rupture of the membranes is a type of disease affecting the female reproductive system. It is defined as a condition characterized by the rupture of chorioamniotic membranes before 37 weeks of gestation. Additionally, this condition is exactly synonymous with PPROM.
Ureteropelvic junction obstruction is a type of urinary tract obstruction characterized by a blockage at the renal pelvis where the kidney attaches to the ureter.

Acquired von Willebrand syndrome (AVWS) is a type of blood coagulation disease and also falls under the category of conditions that, at the very least, exhibit bleeding as a symptom. It is defined as a blood coagulation disease characterized by the development of a defect in clotting in the absence of previous bleeding symptoms, a negative familial history, and its occurrence at a relatively older age. Typically, AVWS develops secondarily to other disorders, including lymphoproliferative, myeloproliferative, cardiovascular, and autoimmune disorders.
Angioimmunoblastic T-cell lymphoma, which is a type of peripheral T-cell lymphoma, is characterized by autoimmune features and has a poor prognosis.

Isolated ectopia lentis is a type of lens disease characterized by abnormal stretching of the zonular fibers, leading to dislocation of the lens, which can range from mild to severe and may progress with age. It is also known by its exact synonyms, IEL and familial ectopia lentis.

Autosomal recessive isolated ectopia lentis 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, isolated ectopia lentis, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an isolated ectopia lentis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ADAMTSL4 gene on chromosome 1q21. Additionally, autosomal recessive isolated ectopia lentis 2 has the exact synonym ECTOL2.

Autosomal Dominant Isolated Ectopia Lentis 1 (ECTOL1) is a type of disease that falls under the broader categories of autosomal dominant diseases, isolated ectopia lentis, and conditions that fundamentally have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as an isolated ectopia lentis that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the FBN1 gene located on chromosome 15q21.

Prinzmetal angina is a type of coronary artery vasospasm characterized by spasms of the coronary arteries that occur while at rest, generally late at night or early in the morning, resulting in severe chest pain with preserved exercise capacity. It has several exact synonyms, including Prinzmetal's angina, Prinzmetal's variant angina, angina inversa, variant angina, and variant angina pectoris.

Multicentric Castleman disease (MCD) is a type of Castleman disease and is also known as MCD, PMCD, multicentric giant lymph node hyperplasia, and plasmablastic multicentric Castleman disease. It is characterized by systemic inflammatory symptoms, polyclonal lymphoproliferation, cytopenias, and multiple organ system dysfunction caused by a cytokine storm often including interleukin-6. Moreover, it is a condition that at least has the symptom of some cytopenia.

Congenital mirror movement disorder is a type of physical and movement disease that is based in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a movement disease characterized by involuntary movements of one side of the body that mirror intentional movements on the opposite side, primarily involving the upper limbs. The disorder has exact synonyms, including familial congenital contralateral synkinesia, familial congenital mirror movements, hereditary congenital contralateral synkinesia, hereditary congenital mirror movements, isolated congenital contralateral synkinesia, and isolated congenital mirror movements.

Postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome (POTS) is classified as a type of monogenic disease, heart conduction disease, and a condition that fundamentally has its basis in genetics. This heart conduction disease is specifically characterized by orthostatic intolerance and is the result of a heterozygous mutation in the SLC6A2 gene on chromosome 16q12.2. POTS is known by several exact synonyms, including familial orthostatic tachycardia due to norepinephrine transporter deficiency, irritable heart, mitral valve prolapse syndrome, neurocirculatory asthenia, orthostatic intolerance, orthostatic intolerance due to NET deficiency, postural tachycardia syndrome due to NET deficiency, and soldier's heart.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 21, also precisely known as SCAR21, acute infantile liver failure-cerebellar ataxia-peripheral sensory motor neuropathy syndrome, and autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 21 with hepatopathy, is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SCYL1 gene on chromosome 11q13.

Spermatogenic failure 9 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by male infertility due to globozoospermia, which involves round-headed spermatozoa lacking an acrosome. This condition has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically in a mutation in the DPY19L2 gene on chromosome 12q14. It is also known by exact synonyms such as globozoospermia, male infertility due to globozoospermia, and male infertility due to round-headed spermatozoa.

Castleman disease is a type of lymphoproliferative syndrome characterized by one or more enlarged lymph nodes containing cells with hyaline-vascular, plasmacytic, or mixed appearance microscopically. It is also known by exact synonyms such as angiofollicular lymph hyperplasia, angiofollicular lymph node hyperplasia, giant lymph node hyperplasia, and lymphoid hamartoma.

Saddan is identified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, a syndrome, and something that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by severe achondroplasia, developmental delay, and acanthosis nigricans, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the FGFR3 gene located on chromosome 4p16. Furthermore, Saddan is precisely synonymous with SADDAN dysplasia and severe achondroplasia with developmental delay and acanthosis nigricans.

Partial trisomy distal 4q is identified as a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome, which is specifically defined as a chromosomal duplication syndrome characterized by a constellation of features. These features include growth deficiency, abnormal muscle tone, intellectual disability, and distinctive craniofacial malformations, all of which are attributed to the duplication of the distal portion of chromosome 4q. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms, including Chromosome 4, Partial Trisomy 4q; Distal 4q Trisomy; Dup(4q) Syndrome, Partial; Duplication 4q Syndrome, Partial; and Partial Trisomy 4q Syndrome.

Camptodactyly tall stature scoliosis hearing loss syndrome, also known exactly as CATSHL syndrome, is a type of autosomal genetic disease and a syndrome that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by camptodactyly, tall stature, scoliosis, and hearing loss, which results from a partial loss of function in the FGFR3 gene located on chromosome 4p16.

Crouzon syndrome acanthosis nigricans syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease, bone disease, and syndrome. It is characterized by Crouzon-like features, premature synostosis of cranial sutures, and acanthosis nigricans, which has a material basis in a heterozygous missense mutation in the FGFR3 gene on chromosome 4p16. This syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: CAN, Crouzon-dermoskeletal syndrome, and Crouzonodermoskeletal syndrome. It is associated with autosomal dominant inheritance and primarily affects the cranial bones.

Epidermal nevus is a type of skin disease, defined as a skin disease characterized by localized epidermal thickening with hyperpigmentation that develops at or shortly after birth. It is also exactly synonymous with nonepidermolytic keratinocytic nevus.

Molybdenum cofactor deficiency type B is a specific type of molybdenum cofactor deficiency, which falls under the category of diseases that have a basis in some structural variant. It is defined by having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MOCS2 gene located on chromosome 5q11. Additionally, this condition is precisely known by several synonyms, including MOCOD type B, MOCODB, combined deficiency of sulfite oxidase, xanthine dehydrogenase, and aldehyde oxidase type B, as well as molybdenum cofactor deficiency complementation group B.

Molybdenum cofactor deficiency type A is a specific form of molybdenum cofactor deficiency. It is characterized by a condition that is fundamentally attributed to some structural variant. This deficiency is defined by having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MOCS1 gene located on chromosome 6p21. Furthermore, Molybdenum cofactor deficiency type A is precisely known by several exact synonyms including MOCOD type A, MOCODA, combined deficiency of sulfite oxidase, xanthine dehydrogenase, and aldehyde oxidase type A, as well as molybdenum cofactor deficiency complementation group A.

Molybdenum cofactor deficiency is a type of metal metabolism disorder characterized by a progressively worsening encephalopathy caused by the absence of molybdenum cofactor. This absence leads to the accumulation of toxic levels of sulphite and neurological damage. It has exact synonyms: MOCOD and combined deficiency of sulfite oxidase, xanthine dehydrogenase, and aldehyde oxidase.

Molybdenum cofactor deficiency type C is a type of molybdenum cofactor deficiency and falls under the category of diseases that have a basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a molybdenum cofactor deficiency that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the GPHN gene on chromosome 14q23. This condition is also exactly synonymous with MOCOD type C, MOCODC, combined deficiency of sulfite oxidase, xanthine dehydrogenase and aldehyde oxidase type C, and molybdenum cofactor deficiency complementation group C.

Dyggve Melchior Clausen disease is an autosomal recessive disease, specifically a type of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia, which is characterized by several factors including clawed fingers, platyspondyly of the spine, abnormalities of the iliac crest, intellectual disability, and mucopolysaccharide in the urine. The disease has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DYM gene on chromosome 18q21. Furthermore, it affects locations such as the vertebral column and fingers. Dyggve Melchior Clausen disease is also known by its exact synonyms, DMC disease and pseudo-Morquio disease type I.

Sepiapterin reductase deficiency is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is categorized as a type of dystonia and is linked to both autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritance. The condition is defined as a dystonia characterized by sustained muscle contractions with diurnal fluctuations, axial hypotonia, oculogyric crises, delays in motor and cognitive development, along with severe dopamine and serotonin deficiencies due to a mutation in the SPR gene on chromosome 2p, leading to sepiapterin reductase deficiency. It is also known by its exact synonyms: DRD due to SRD, SPR deficiency, SRD, and dopa-responsive dystonia due to sepiapterin reductase deficiency.

Subcortical band heterotopia is a type of congenital nervous system abnormality defined as a congenital nervous system abnormality characterized by the migration of neurons to ectopic locations in the brain, where the neurons form areas that appear as band-like clusters of white tissue underneath the gray tissue of the cerebral cortex. It has several exact synonyms, including HeCo, band heterotopia, double cortex syndrome, heterotopic cortex, and subcortical laminar heterotopia.

Autosomal dominant sensory ataxia 1 (ADSA), also known exactly as SNAX1, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, hereditary ataxia, and is defined by a condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This hereditary ataxia is characterized by gait difficulty and instability, particularly in dark conditions, resulting from sensory loss in the extremities without cerebellar involvement. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the RNF170 gene on chromosome 8.

French Canadian Leigh disease is a type of Cytochrome C oxidase deficiency disease characterized by metabolic and/or neurological crises, chronic hyperlactataemia, hypotonia, ataxia, mild facial dysmorphism, delayed development, and the development of lesions in the brainstem and basal ganglia. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in LRPPRC on 2p21. It is also known by several exact synonyms including French Canadian type COX deficiency, French Canadian type Leigh syndrome, French Canadian type cytochrome c oxidase deficiency, Saguenay Lac Saint Jean type COX deficiency, Saguenay Lac Saint Jean type Leigh syndrome, and mitochondrial complex IV deficiency nuclear type 5.

Familial Hemiplegic Migraine 1 (FHM1) is a type of Familial Hemiplegic Migraine. It is commonly associated with cerebellar degeneration and is defined as a familial hemiplegic migraine with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CACNA1A gene on chromosome 19p13. FHM1 is also known by its exact synonyms: MHP1 and Familial Hemiplegic Migraine 1 with Progressive Cerebellar Ataxia.

Familial Hemiplegic Migraine 2 is a type of Familial Hemiplegic Migraine, defined by a familial hemiplegic migraine that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in ATP1A2 on 1q23.2. It is exactly synonymous with FHM2, Familial Hemiplegic Migraine-2, and MHP2.

Familial Hemiplegic Migraine 3 is a type of Familial Hemiplegic Migraine. This specific subtype is defined as a familial hemiplegic migraine that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SCN1A gene located on chromosome 2q24.3. Furthermore, Familial Hemiplegic Migraine 3 is precisely synonymized with FHM3 and MHP3.

Myopathy lactic acidosis and sideroblastic anemia 3 (MLASA3) is a type of myopathy lactic acidosis and sideroblastic anemia. It is defined as a myopathy, lactic acidosis, and sideroblastic anemia characterized by early infantile onset of transfusion-dependent sideroblastic anemia with failure to thrive, hearing loss, epilepsy, stroke-like episodes, and severe developmental delay. This condition has a material basis in heteroplasmic mutation in the MTATP6 gene, encoded by nucleotides 8527-9207 of the mitochondrial genome.

Myopathy, lactic acidosis, and sideroblastic anemia 1 is a type of myopathy, lactic acidosis, and sideroblastic anemia. It is defined as a myopathy, lactic acidosis, and sideroblastic anemia that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PUS1 gene on chromosome 12q24. Additionally, it has the exact synonym MLASA1.

Myopathy lactic acidosis and sideroblastic anemia 2 (MLASA2) is a type of myopathy lactic acidosis and sideroblastic anemia. It is defined as a myopathy, lactic acidosis, and sideroblastic anemia characterized by marked phenotypic variability in time of onset and severity of symptoms. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the YARS2 gene located on 12p11.21.

Distal myopathy with anterior tibial onset, which has the exact synonyms DMAT and distal muscular dystrophy with anterior tibial onset, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of distal myopathy. This condition is characterized by its origins in autosomal recessive inheritance and typically begins during young adulthood. The definition of distal myopathy with anterior tibial onset describes it as a distal myopathy that manifests between the ages of 14 and 28, initially affecting the anterior tibial muscles before progressing to both upper and lower proximal muscles. This progression is due to a homozygous mutation in the gene encoding dysferlin (DYSF) located on chromosome 2p13.

Myofibrillar myopathy 9 is a type of myofibrillar myopathy that is characterized by adult onset of slowly progressive muscle weakness involving the diaphragm and resulting in respiratory insufficiency. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TTN gene on chromosome 2q31. It exhibits symptoms such as muscle weakness and progressive weakness. Myofibrillar myopathy 9 is also known by several exact synonyms, including Edstrom myopathy, HIBM-ERF, HMERF, Hereditary inclusion body myopathy with early respiratory failure, MFM-titinopathy, MFM9, MPRM, Myofibrillar myopathy-titinopathy, autosomal dominant distal myopathy with early respiratory failure, hereditary myopathy with early respiratory failure, myofibrillar myopathy 9 with early respiratory failure, and proximal myopathy with early respiratory muscle involvement.

Distal myopathy 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and distal myopathy, which at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and its existence starts during adult onset. It is characterized by adult onset of slowly progressive distal muscular weakness and atrophy affecting the upper and lower limbs, leading to difficulties using the hands and walking. This condition shows significant linkage to 2 distinct regions on chromosomes 8p22-q11 and 12q13-q22 and results from a heterozygous mutation in the HNRNPA1 gene on chromosome 12q13. Distal myopathy 3 is also known by its exact synonyms: MPD3, distal muscular dystrophy 3, and distal myopathy type 3.

Distal myopathy 4 is a type of distal myopathy, which is defined as a distal myopathy that has its material basis in heterozygous mutation in the FLNC gene on chromosome 7q32. It is exactly synonymous with MPD4, distal ABD-filaminopathy, distal muscular dystrophy 4, and distal myopathy with posterior leg and anterior hand involvement.

Distal myopathy Tateyama type is a type of distal myopathy and also an autosomal dominant disease, which means it is a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined by having a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the caveolin-3 gene (CAV3) located on chromosome 3p25. Additionally, distal myopathy Tateyama type is exactly synonymous with distal muscular dystrophy Tateyama type.

Facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy 1 is a type of facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy, defined by a contraction of the D4Z4 macrosatellite repeat in the subtelomeric region of chromosome 4q35. It is exactly synonymous with FSHD1, facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy type 1, and facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy type 1A.

Facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy 2 (FSHD2), also known as facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy 1B and facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy type 2, is a specific type of facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy and a digenic disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally involves digenic inheritance. More precisely, FSHD2 is defined by a digenic inheritance involving a heterozygous mutation in the SMCHD1 gene located on chromosome 18p11.32 and a specific haplotype on chromosome 4 that allows for DUX4 expression.

Autosomal dominant adult onset proximal spinal muscular atrophy is a type of spinal muscular atrophy that exhibits symptoms such as muscle weakness and begins during adult onset. It is defined as a spinal muscular atrophy characterized by the adult onset of slowly progressive, proximal muscular weakness with fasciculations and absent or hypoactive deep tendon reflexes, without bulbar or pyramidal involvement. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in VAPB on chromosome 20q13. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including Finkel disease, Finkel late-adult type SMA, SMAFK, autosomal dominant adult proximal spinal muscular atrophy, autosomal dominant adult-onset proximal SMA, and autosomal dominant late-onset spinal muscular atrophy, Finkel type.

Erythrokeratodermia variabilis et progressiva 1 is a type of erythrokeratodermia variabilis, and it also falls under the category of both autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive diseases. It has a material basis in some forms of both autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, erythrokeratodermia variabilis et progressiva 1 is defined as an erythrokeratodermia variabilis that results from heterozygous, homozygous, or compound heterozygous mutation in the GJB3 gene located on chromosome 1p34.3.

X-linked distal spinal muscular atrophy 3 is a type of X-linked recessive disease and a form of spinal muscular atrophy that fundamentally has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance and exhibits symptoms including muscle weakness. It is characterized as a spinal muscular atrophy involving slowly progressive atrophy and weakness of the distal muscles of the hands and feet, notable for the absence of cognitive, pyramidal, or sensory impairment, with its material basis in homozygous or hemizygous mutations in the ATP7A gene located on Xq21.1. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms: ATP7A-related distal motor neuropathy, DSMAX, SMAX3, X-linked dHMN3, X-linked dSMA3, X-linked distal hereditary motor neuropathy type 3, and X-linked recessive distal spinal muscular atrophy.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy is a type of autosomal recessive disease, spinal muscular atrophy, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spinal muscular atrophy that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy has an exact synonym, autosomal recessive distal spinal muscular atrophy.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy is a type of autosomal dominant disease, spinal muscular atrophy, and is characterized as something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a spinal muscular atrophy that is characterized by progressive distal motor weakness and muscular atrophy of the peripheral nervous system without sensory impairment. This condition is caused by anterior horn cell degeneration and has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy is also exactly known as autosomal dominant dHMN, autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuropathy, and autosomal dominant distal spinal muscular atrophy.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 7 (DHMN7A) is a specific type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy. It is characterized by an autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy that exhibits slowly progressive distal atrophy and weakness, initially affecting the upper limbs and subsequently the lower limbs, as well as vocal cord paresis. The condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SLC5A7 gene located on chromosome 2q12.3. This condition is notable for at least having symptoms such as muscle weakness. Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 7 is also known by several exact synonyms, including DHMN7A, DHMNVPy, HMN VIIA, HMN7A, Harper-Young myopathy, dHMN7, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 7, distal hereditary motor neuropathy type VIIA, distal spinal muscular atrophy with vocal cord paralysis, and distal spinal muscular atrophy with vocal cord paralysis type 7A.

Autosomal Dominant Distal Hereditary Motor Neuronopathy 1 (AD-DHMN1) is a type of Autosomal Dominant Distal Hereditary Motor Neuronopathy and is characterized by progressive distal motor weakness and muscular atrophy of the peripheral nervous system without sensory impairment. This condition is notable for being caused by anterior horn cell degeneration, which in turn is due to a heterozygous 1.35-Mb DNA insertion on chromosome 7q34-q36.2. This structural variant results in the production of a novel gene-intergenic fusion transcript, UBE3C-IF. Moreover, AD-DHMN1 is known to present symptoms such as muscle weakness. It is also referred to by several exact synonyms including HMN I, Autosomal Dominant Distal Juvenile Spinal Muscular Atrophy Type 1, dHMN1, Distal Hereditary Motor Neuronopathy Type 1, Distal Hereditary Motor Neuropathy Type I, and Spinal Charcot-Marie-Tooth Disease 1.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 14 is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy. It is defined as an autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DCTN1 gene located on chromosome 2p13.1. This condition is also exactly synonymous with several terms, including DHMN7B, HMN VIIB, HMN7B, Harper-Young myopathy, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 7B, distal hereditary motor neuropathy type VIIB, and distal spinal muscular atrophy with vocal cord paralysis type 7B.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 5 is a specific type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy, which is characterized by the onset of distal muscle weakness and atrophy predominantly affecting the upper limbs in the first few decades of life. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GARS gene on chromosome 7p14 and is also associated with symptoms including muscle weakness. It is known by several exact synonyms, including DHMN5, DSMAV, HMN5, distal HMN V, distal HMN VA, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 5, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 5A, distal hereditary motor neuropathy type V, distal spinal muscular atrophy type V, distal spinal muscular atrophy type VA, and distal spinal muscular atrophy with upper limb predominance.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 12 is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy. It is defined as an autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the REEP1 gene on 2p11.2. This condition is also exactly synonymous with distal HMN VB, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 5B, and distal spinal muscular atrophy type VB.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 2 is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy, which is also a type of condition that, at a minimum, presents with the symptom of muscle weakness. It is defined as an autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy characterized by the onset of slowly progressive distal limb weakness and atrophy occurring between the second and fifth decades of life. This condition is known by several exact synonyms: HMN II, HMN IIA, HMN2, HMN2A, autosomal dominant adult spinal muscular atrophy IIA, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 2, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 2A, distal hereditary motor neuropathy type II, distal hereditary motor neuropathy type IIA, and spinal Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease IIA.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 3 is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy. It is defined as an autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding heat-shock 27-kD protein-1 (HSPB1) on chromosome 7q11.23. Furthermore, autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 3 is also exactly synonymous with HMN IIB, HMN2B, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 2B, and distal hereditary motor neuropathy type IIB.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 4 is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy, defined by a distal hereditary motor neuropathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the HSPB3 gene on chromosome 5q11.2. It is also known by its exact synonyms: DHMN2C, HMN IIC, HMN2C, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 2C, and distal hereditary motor neuropathy type IIC.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 6 is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy, characterized by a distal hereditary motor neuropathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FBXO38 gene on chromosome 5q32. It is also precisely known as HMN IID, HMN2D, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 2D, distal hereditary motor neuropathy type IID, and distal spinal muscular atrophy with calf predominance.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 3 is a type of autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy and is also characterized as a condition that at least has the symptom of muscle weakness. It is defined as an autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy characterized by the juvenile onset of distal muscle weakness and wasting with variable severity, which has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in a 2.6-cM region of chromosome 11q13.3. This condition is exactly synonymous with autosomal recessive distal spinal muscular atrophy type 3, dHMN3 and dHMN4, dSMA3, and distal hereditary motor neuropathy type 3 and type 4, implying these terms refer to the same condition.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 9 is a specific type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy, which is also known by its exact synonyms: DHMN9, HMN9, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 9, and distal hereditary motor neuropathy type IX. This condition is characterized by its juvenile onset of a slowly progressing distal muscle weakness and atrophy that affects both the lower and upper limbs. The basis of this disorder is a heterozygous mutation in the WARS gene located on chromosome 14q32.2. Additionally, autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 9 is associated with symptoms including muscle weakness and progressive weakness.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 4 is a type of autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy, which is characterized by symptoms such as muscle weakness and progressive weakness. It is defined as an autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy with an onset in early childhood, exhibiting rapidly progressing proximal muscle weakness with early involvement of foot and hand muscles. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PLEKHG5 gene on chromosome 1p36.31. Additionally, autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 4 is known by several exact synonyms, including DSMA4, autosomal recessive distal spinal muscular atrophy type 4, autosomal recessive lower motor neuron disease with childhood onset, and distal spinal muscular atrophy type 4.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 5 (dHMN5) is a type of autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy that has symptoms including muscle weakness and progressive weakness. It is defined as an autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy characterized by the young adult onset of slowly progressive distal muscle weakness and atrophy, resulting in gait impairment and loss of reflexes. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in DNAJB2 on chromosome 2q35. dHMN5 is also known by its exact synonyms: DSMA5, autosomal recessive distal spinal muscular atrophy type 5, distal spinal muscular atrophy type 5, young adult-onset dHMN, and young adult-onset distal hereditary motor neuropathy.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 8 is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy, and it also falls into a category of conditions that typically exhibit muscle weakness as a symptom. This specific disorder is defined as an autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy characterized by congenital, non-progressive, predominantly distal, lower limb muscle weakness and atrophy with variable severity. Its material basis lies in a heterozygous mutation in the TRPV4 gene located on chromosome 12q24.11. Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 8 is known by several exact synonyms, including DHMN8, HMN8, autosomal dominant benign distal spinal muscular atrophy, autosomal dominant congenital benign spinal muscular atrophy, congenital benign spinal muscular atrophy with contractures, congenital nonprogressive spinal muscular atrophy, distal hereditary motor neuronopathy type 8, and distal hereditary motor neuropathy type VIII.

Autosomal recessive centronuclear myopathy is a type of autosomal recessive disease, centronuclear myopathy, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a centronuclear myopathy that has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, autosomal recessive centronuclear myopathy has the exact synonym AR-CNM.

Autosomal dominant centronuclear myopathy (AD-CNM) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of centronuclear myopathy. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Moreover, it is defined as a centronuclear myopathy that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Friedreich ataxia 1 is a type of Friedreich ataxia and has the definition: A Friedreich ataxia that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in FXN on 9q21.1. Additionally, it has exact synonyms FA1 and FRDA1.

Friedreich ataxia 2 is a type of Friedreich ataxia and is defined as a Friedreich ataxia that has its material basis in a mutation in the 9p23-p11 chromosome region. Additionally, it has the exact synonym FRDA2.

Centronuclear myopathy 2 is a type of autosomal recessive centronuclear myopathy and has the exact synonym CNM2. It is defined as an autosomal recessive centronuclear myopathy that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in BIN1 on chromosome 2q14.3.

Centronuclear myopathy 6 with fiber type disproportion is a type of autosomal recessive centronuclear myopathy and is exactly synonymous with CNM6. It is defined as an autosomal recessive centronuclear myopathy that is characterized by onset in infancy or early childhood of slowly progressive centronuclear myopathy. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ZAK gene located on chromosome 2q31.1.

Centronuclear myopathy 5, which is a type of autosomal recessive centronuclear myopathy, is characterized by severe neonatal hypotonia, respiratory insufficiency, and difficulty feeding. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in SPEG on chromosome 2q35. Additionally, centronuclear myopathy 5 is exactly synonymous with CNM5.

Centronuclear myopathy 1, also known exactly as CNM1, is a type of autosomal dominant centronuclear myopathy. It is characterized by slowly progressive muscle wasting and weakness, primarily affecting the limb girdle, trunk, and neck muscles. This condition arises from a heterozygous mutation in DNM2 on chromosome 19p13.2. Furthermore, CNM1 exhibits symptoms including muscle weakness and progressive weakness.

Centronuclear myopathy 4 is a type of autosomal dominant centronuclear myopathy and has an exact synonym, CNM4. It is defined as an autosomal dominant centronuclear myopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in CCDC78 on 16p13.3.

Centronuclear myopathy X-linked is a type of centronuclear myopathy defined by its material basis in X-linked inheritance of mutations in MTM1 on Xq28. It is exactly synonymous with CNMX, MTM1, X-linked myotubular myopathy, XLCNM, XLMTM, and myotubular myopathy 1.

X-linked congenital myopathy with fiber type disproportion is a type of congenital myopathy 4a, known by its exact synonym CFTDX. This condition is characterized by a range of symptoms including ptosis and facial weakness. It is also defined by a congenital fiber-type disproportion, which is evident through clinical features such as bilateral ptosis, facial weakness, impaired suckling, generalized hypotonia, and respiratory insufficiency. The basis of this disease lies in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth, with its material basis rooted in a mutation located in the chromosome region Xq13.1-q22.1.

Chromosome 3 linked frontotemporal dementia is a specific type of frontotemporal dementia that is characterized by a heterozygous mutation in CHMP2B located on 3p11.2. This condition is also precisely known by other names including CHMP2B-related frontotemporal dementia, FTD3, and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 17.

Sveinsson chorioretinal atrophy is a type of eye disease characterized by the presence in the fundus of progressive bilateral retinal and choroidal atrophy leading to central vision loss. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in TEAD1 on chromosome 11p15.3. It is also exactly known as HPCD, SCRA, atrophia areata, helicoid peripapillary chorioretinal degeneration, and peripapillary chorioretinal degeneration, Icelandic type.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A is a type of autosomal recessive disease, muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by symptoms of muscle weakness and has a basis in some abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. This condition is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy characterized by cobblestone lissencephaly, muscle weakness, and brain and eye anomalies resulting from a defect in alpha-dystroglycan post-translational processing. It has exact synonyms, including MDDGA, congenital muscular alpha-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies, and klissencephaly type 2 with muscular and ocular involvement.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A11 is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A, and it is also a type of condition that has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in B3GALNT2 on 1q42.3. This condition has exact synonyms, including MDDGA11, Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease B3GALNT2-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A11.

Congenital Muscular Dystrophy Dystroglycanopathy Type A8 is a specific type of Congenital Muscular Dystrophy Dystroglycanopathy Type A and also falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the POMGNT2 gene located on chromosome 3p22.1. This condition is exactly synonymous with MDDGA8, Walker-Warburg Syndrome or Muscle-Eye-Brain Disease GTDC2-related, and Congenital Muscular Dystrophy-Dystroglycanopathy with Brain and Eye Anomalies Type A8.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A9 is classified as a type of congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A, and it is also a type of condition that has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. This condition is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DAG1 gene located on chromosome 3p21.31. Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A9 has several exact synonyms, including MDDGA9, Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease DAG1-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A9.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy A14 is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A, and it also represents a condition that stems from some abnormality in prenatal development or birth. This specific disorder, congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy A14, is defined by having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in GMPPB on chromosome 3p21.31. It is precisely synonymous with MDDGA14, Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease GMPPB-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A14.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy A7 is a specific type of congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A. It is also identified as a condition that arises due to abnormalities in prenatal development or at birth. This particular disorder is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ISPD gene located on chromosome 7p21.2-p21.1. It is exactly synonymous with MDDGA7, Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease ISPD-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A7.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A12 is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A and falls under the broader category of diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the POMK gene on chromosome 8p11.21. This condition is precisely known by several exact synonyms, including MDDGA12, Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease POMK-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A12.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A3 is a subtype of congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A. It falls under the category of diseases that originate from abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. The condition is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the POMGNT1 gene located on chromosome 1p34.1. It is precisely synonymous with MDDGA3, and also known as Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease, POMGNT1-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A3.

Congenital Muscular Dystrophy Dystroglycanopathy Type A1 is a subtype of Congenital Muscular Dystrophy Dystroglycanopathy Type A and is classified as a condition that originates from some abnormality in prenatal development or birth. This specific type, known as Congenital Muscular Dystrophy-Dystroglycanopathy Type A1, is defined by its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the POMT1 gene located on chromosome 9q34.13. Additionally, it carries exact synonyms such as MDDGA1, Walker-Warburg syndrome or Muscle-Eye-Brain Disease, POMT1-related, and Congenital Muscular Dystrophy-Dystroglycanopathy with Brain and Eye Anomalies Type A1, thereby highlighting its diverse clinical manifestations and genetic underpinnings.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A13 is a specific type of congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A and falls into the category of diseases with a basis in abnormal prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the B4GAT1 gene located on chromosome 11q13.2. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms including MDDGA13, Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease related to both B3GNT1 and B4GNT1, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A13.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A10 is a subtype of congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A, and it also falls under the category of diseases that originate from abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. This particular disorder is defined by having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RXYLT1 gene located on chromosome 12q14.2. Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A10 is exactly synonymous with MDDGA10, Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease, TMEM5-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A10.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A2 is a subtype of congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A, and it represents a condition that arises due to some abnormality in prenatal development or birth. This specific type, congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A2, is defined by being a congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the POMT2 gene located on chromosome 14q24.3. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including MDDGA2, Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease, POMT2-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A2.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A5 is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A, and it is also a type of condition that has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Its definition is a congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FKRP gene located on chromosome 19q13.32. Moreover, congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A5 is exactly synonymous with MDDGA5, Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease, FKRP-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A5.

Congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type a6 is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type A and also falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. This specific condition, congenital muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type a6, is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy type A that arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in LARGE on 22q12.3. It is exactly synonymous with MDDGA6, Walker-Warburg syndrome or muscle-eye-brain disease, LARGE-related, and congenital muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy with brain and eye anomalies type A6, indicating its diverse yet specific diagnostic labels.

Acromicric dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of severe short stature, short hands and feet, joint limitations, mild facial anomalies, skin thickening, and bone abnormalities including delayed bone age, cone-shaped epiphyses, shortened long tubular bones, and ovoid vertebral bodies. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FBN1 gene located on chromosome 15q21.1. Acromicric dysplasia is also exactly synonymous with ACMICD and acromicric skeletal dysplasia.

Palmoplantar keratoderma and congenital alopecia 1 is identified as a type of physical disorder, ectodermal dysplasia, and is considered a condition that emerges due to some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. The definition of palmoplantar keratoderma and congenital alopecia 1 is an ectodermal dysplasia characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of severe hyperkeratosis, congenital alopecia, and in some patients, nail anomalies. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the GJA1 gene located on chromosome 6q22.31. It is also known by several exact synonyms: PPK-CA, Stevanovic type; PPKCA Stevanovic type; PPKCA1; autosomal dominant palmoplantar hyperkeratosis and congenital alopecia; autosomal dominant palmoplantar keratoderma and congenital alopecia; keratoderma-hypotrichosis-leukonychia totalis syndrome; and palmoplantar keratoderma and congenital alopecia, Stevanovic type.

Palmoplantar keratoderma and congenital alopecia 2 is classified as a type of physical disorder, an ectodermal dysplasia, and a condition that stems from some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as an ectodermal dysplasia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of alopecia, progressive palmoplantar hyperkeratosis resulting in sclerodactyly, and is usually associated with cataracts and pseudoainhum formation. This condition is precisely identified by several exact synonyms including CASS, PPK-CA Wallis type, PPKCA Wallis type, PPKCA2, autosomal recessive palmoplantar hyperkeratosis and congenital alopecia, autosomal recessive palmoplantar keratoderma and congenital alopecia, cataract-alopecia-sclerodactyly syndrome, and palmoplantar keratoderma and congenital alopecia, Wallis type.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis parkinsonism dementia complex 1 is a type of neurodegenerative disease characterized by chronic, progressive amyotrophic lateral sclerosis and parkinsonism-dementia. This disease's susceptibility is influenced by a heterozygous mutation in TRPM7 on chromosome 15q21.2. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including ALS-PDC, Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis-parkinsonism-dementia of Guam syndrome, Guam disease, Lytico-Bodig disease, PDALS, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis-parkinsonism/dementia complex of Guam, and parkinsonism-dementia-ALS complex.

Hypertension and brachydactyly syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease, syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by brachydactyly type E, severe salt-independent but age-dependent hypertension, an increased fibroblast growth rate, neurovascular contact at the rostral-ventrolateral medulla, altered baroreflex blood pressure regulation, and an increased risk of stroke when untreated. This syndrome has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in PDE3A on chromosome 12p12.2. Hypertension and brachydactyly syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: Bilginturan brachydactyly, Bilginturan syndrome, HTNB, brachydactyly with hypertension, and type E brachydactyly with short stature and hypertension.

Cerebrocostomandibular syndrome is a type of syndrome and autosomal dominant disease that at least has its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by severe micrognathia, posterior rib and palate defects, and often intellectual disability. This syndrome has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in SNRPB on 20p13. Moreover, cerebrocostomandibular syndrome has exact synonyms including CCM syndrome, CCMS, cerebro-costo-mandibular syndrome, and rib gap defects with micrognathia.

Uveal coloboma cleft lip and palate intellectual disability is a syndrome that is an autosomal dominant disease, which means it has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by uveal coloboma, variable degrees of orofacial clefting, intellectual disability, and hearing impairment, and it has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the YAP1 gene located on chromosome 11q22.1. It is known by several exact synonyms, including COB1, Uveal coloboma-cleft lip/palate-mental retardation syndrome, and coloboma-microphthalmos syndrome. Additionally, it is referred to as coloboma-microphthalmos syndrome associated with sensorineural hearing loss, hematuria, and cleft lip/palate, as well as ocular coloboma with or without hearing impairment, cleft lip/palate, and/or mental retardation.

Parkinson's disease 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, late-onset Parkinson's disease, and it is characterized by having at least a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a late-onset Parkinson's disease with a mean age of onset of 59 years, which is due to a mutation in a locus in the 2p13 chromosome region. Parkinson's disease 3 is also known by several exact synonyms, including PARK3, Parkinson disease 3, autosomal dominant Lewy body Parkinson disease 3, and autosomal dominant Parkinson disease 3.

Parkinson's disease 21 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also a type of late-onset Parkinson's disease. It is characterized by something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, Parkinson's disease 21 is defined as a late-onset Parkinson's disease characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance with a mean age of onset at 67 years. It has exact synonyms, including PARK21 and Parkinson disease 21.

@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:vestibular_schwannomatosis rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty :has_material_basis_in ;
            owl:someValuesFrom :autosomal_dominant_inheritance ],
        :schwannomatosis ;
    :has_definition "A schwannomatosis characterized by bilateral vestibular schwannomas or a combination of unilateral vestibular schwannomas, non-vestibular schwannomas, meningiomas, ependymomas, and specific eye abnormalities that has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in the NF2 gene on chromosome 22q12.2. Eye abnormalities include juvenile subcapsular or cortical cataract, epiretinal membrane in a person less than 40 years old, and retinal hamartoma. This disease has been revised by international consensus. It was previously referred to as neurofibromatosis 2." ;
    :has_exact_match "GARD:7193",
        "ICD10CM:Q85.02",
        "ICD9CM:237.72",
        "MESH:D016518",
        "NCI:C3274",
        "OMIM:101000",
        "ORDO:637",
        "SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:92503002",
        "UMLS_CUI:C0027832" ;
    :has_exact_synonym "NF2-related schwannomatosis",
        "SWN3",
        "SWNV",
        "acoustic neurofibromatosis",
        "neurofibromatosis 2",
        "schwannomatosis 3",
        "ACN"@en,
        "BANF"@en,
        "NF2"@en,
        "bilateral acoustic neurinoma"@en,
        "bilateral acoustic neurofibromatosis"@en,
        "bilateral acoustic schwannomas"@en,
        "central neurofibromatosis"@en,
        "familial acoustic neuromas"@en,
        "neurofibromatosis type II"@en ;
    :has_narrower_match "ORDO:634475" .
text:
Vestibular schwannomatosis is a type of schwannomatosis that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by bilateral vestibular schwannomas or a combination of unilateral vestibular schwannomas, non-vestibular schwannomas, meningiomas, ependymomas, and specific eye abnormalities. These eye abnormalities include juvenile subcapsular or cortical cataract, epiretinal membrane in a person less than 40 years old, and retinal hamartoma. The condition results from a heterozygous mutation in the NF2 gene on chromosome 22q12.2, and has been revised by international consensus, previously referred to as neurofibromatosis 2.

Vestibular schwannomatosis is also known by several exact synonyms: ACN, BANF, NF2, NF2-related schwannomatosis, SWN3, SWNV, acoustic neurofibromatosis, bilateral acoustic neurinoma, bilateral acoustic neurofibromatosis, bilateral acoustic schwannomas, central neurofibromatosis, familial acoustic neuromas, neurofibromatosis 2, neurofibromatosis type II, and schwannomatosis 3. 

Moreover, vestibular schwannomatosis matches exactly with multiple codes across various medical classification systems and databases: GARD:7193, ICD10CM:Q85.02, ICD9CM:237.72, MESH:D016518, NCI:C3274, OMIM:101000, ORDO:637, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:92503002, and UMLS_CUI:C0027832. Additionally, it has a narrower match with ORDO:634475.

Neurofibromatosis 1 is a type of neurofibromatosis and a condition that typically has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by multiple cafe-au-lait macules, skin fold freckling, neurofibromas, optic gliomas, Lisch nodules or choroidal abnormalities in the eye, or a specific bone abnormality, all of which have a material basis in the NF1 gene located on chromosome 17q11.2. Notable bone abnormalities include distinctive osseous lesions such as sphenoid dysplasia, anterolateral bowing of the tibia, or pseudarthrosis of a long bone. Neurofibromatosis 1 is also known by several exact synonyms, including NF1, Peripheral Neurofibromatosis, Recklinghausen's Neurofibromatosis, Neurofibromatosis Type I, and von Recklinghausen Disease. Furthermore, Neurofibromatosis 1 is precisely matched with several medical coding systems and databases, including ICD10CM:Q85.01, ICD9CM:237.71, MESH:D009456, NCI:C3273, OMIM:162200, ORDO:636, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:92824003, and UMLS_CUI:C0027831.

Glutaric acidemia I is a type of autosomal recessive disease, organic acidemia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by impaired lysine, hydroxylysine, and tryptophan metabolism, increased urinary excretion of glutaric acid, and accumulation of 3-hydroxyglutaric and glutaric acid. This leads to striatal injury and a severe dystonic dyskinetic movement disorder, which is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GCDH gene on chromosome 19p13. Glutaric acidemia I is also known by several exact synonyms including GA1, glutaric academia type 1, glutaric aciduria 1, glutaric aciduria type I, glutaryl-CoA dehydrogenase deficiency, and glutaryl-coenzyme A dehydrogenase deficiency.

Mc Kusick Kaufman syndrome is a type of syndrome, specifically an autosomal recessive disease. It also falls into the category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by a neonatal onset of genitourinary malformations, particularly hydrometrocolpos, polydactyly, and, more rarely, heart or gastrointestinal malformations. The condition's material basis is in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MKKS gene located on 20p12.2. Additionally, Mc Kusick Kaufman syndrome is known by several exact synonyms, including HMCS, Kaufman McKusick syndrome, MKKS, hydrometrocolpos syndrome, hydrometrocolpos, postaxial polydactyly, and congenital heart malformation, as well as hydrometrocolpos-postaxial polydactyly syndrome.

Hyperferritinemia cataract syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome, specifically one that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by elevated circulating levels of ferritin without iron overload and early onset cataracts, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the iron responsive element in the 5-prime noncoding region of FTL on chromosome 19q13.33. This syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms: Bonneau-Beaumont syndrome, HHCS, HRFTC, cataract-hyperferritinemia syndrome, hereditary hyperferritinemia with congenital cataracts, hereditary hyperferritinemia-cataract syndrome, and hyperferritinemia with or without cataract.

Gamma glutamyl transpeptidase deficiency is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal recessive disease, an amino acid metabolic disorder, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is characterized by the accumulation of glutathione in the plasma and urine, a situation that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in GGT1 on chromosome 22q11.23. Furthermore, gamma glutamyl transpeptidase deficiency is known by several exact synonyms, including GGT deficiency, GGT1 deficiency, GTG deficiency, gamma-glutamyl transferase deficiency, and glutathionuria.

Pentosuria is a type of autosomal recessive disease and an amino acid metabolic disorder, which also falls under conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by the excretion of excess pentose L-xylulose (1-4 g/day) in the urine due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DCXR gene located on chromosome 17q25.3. Pentosuria is known by several exact synonyms, including L-xylulose reductase deficiency, L-xylulosuria, PNTSU, essential pentosuria, and xylitol dehydrogenase deficiency.

Postaxial acrofacial dysostosis is a type of autosomal recessive disease, syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by severe micrognathia, cleft lip and/or palate, hypoplasia or aplasia of the postaxial elements of the limbs, coloboma of the eyelids, cup-shaped ears, and supernumerary nipples. This syndrome has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in DHODH on 16q22.2. Furthermore, postaxial acrofacial dysostosis is exactly synonymous with Miller syndrome, POADS, Postaxial acrodysostosis, acrofacial dysostosis, Genee-Wiedmann type, and mandibulofacial dysostosis with postaxial limb anomalies.

Phosphoribosylpyrophosphate synthetase superactivity, also exactly known as PRPP synthetase superactivity and PRPS1 superactivity, is a type of X-linked recessive disease, inherited metabolic disorder, and something that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as an inherited metabolic disorder characterized by increased synthesis of phosphoribosylpyrophosphate resulting in increased production of uric acid and purine. This condition has its material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance of mutations in PRPS1 on Xq22.3 that result in increased activity of the gene. The mild form of the disease has late-juvenile or early adult onset, whereas the more severe form has infantile or early-childhood onset.

Fumarase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the category of amino acid metabolic disorders. It is characterized by being a condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, fumarase deficiency is defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder marked by symptoms such as metabolic acidosis, elevated levels of fumaric acid in the urine, early-onset hypotonia, profound psychomotor retardation, and brain abnormalities. These manifestations have their material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FH gene located on chromosome 1q43. Furthermore, fumarase deficiency is exactly synonymous with FMRD and fumaric aciduria.

Infantile cerebral and cerebellar atrophy with postnatal progressive microcephaly is a type of autosomal recessive disease, brain disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by cerebral and cerebellar atrophy, postnatal progressive microcephaly, and intellectual disability that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in MED17 on 11q21. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: postnatal progressive microcephaly, seizures, and brain atrophy.

Combined malonic and methylmalonic acidemia (CMAMMA), also known as combined malonic and methylmalonic aciduria, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and organic acidemia. It is characterized by elevated levels of methylmalonic acid and malonic acid in body fluids, which typically result in developmental delay and failure to thrive in children, as well as neurological symptoms in adults. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ACSF3 gene located on chromosome 16q24.3. Furthermore, combined malonic and methylmalonic acidemia is associated with autosomal recessive inheritance and has symptoms including failure to thrive.

Ruijs Aalfs syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which is a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by genomic instability and susceptibility toward early onset hepatocellular carcinoma, with this condition having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in SPRTN on 1q42.2. Additionally, Ruijs Aalfs syndrome has an exact synonym: progeroid features-hepatocellular carcinoma predisposition syndrome.

Boucher Neuhauser Syndrome is a type of syndrome and a specific kind of autosomal recessive disease, which means it at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by spinocerebellar ataxia, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, and chorioretinal dystrophy, stemming from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PNPLA6 gene located on chromosome 19p13.2. Furthermore, it is also known by its exact synonym, Ataxia-Hypogonadism-Choroidal Dystrophy Syndrome.

Geroderma osteodysplasticum is a syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases and is a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is specifically characterized by a collection of symptoms including lax and wrinkled skin, progeroid features, hip dislocation, joint laxity, severe short stature or dwarfism, severe osteoporosis, vertebral abnormalities, spontaneous fractures, developmental delay, and mild intellectual deficit. The underlying cause of these symptoms is found to be homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GORAB gene located on chromosome 1q24.2. Furthermore, Geroderma osteodysplasticum is known by several exact synonyms, including GO, Walt Disney dwarfism, geroderma osteodysplastica, and gerodermia osteodysplastica.

Hyaline body myopathy is a type of congenital myopathy and is also known exactly as myosin storage myopathy. It is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by the accumulation of ATPase and antibody-positive myosin in hyaline subsarcolemmal bodies in type I muscle fibers, leading to a variable development of muscle weakness. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the MYH7 gene located on 14q11.2.

Autosomal recessive hyaline body myopathy is a type of autosomal recessive disease, hyaline body myopathy, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a hyaline body myopathy that has its material basis in compound heterozygous or homozygous mutation in MYH7 on chromosome 14q11.2. Furthermore, autosomal recessive hyaline body myopathy is exactly synonymous with MSMB, Myopathy, myosin storage, autosomal recessive, and congenital myopathy 7B.

Autosomal dominant hyaline body myopathy (ADHBM), also known precisely as MSMA, Myopathy, myosin storage, autosomal dominant, congenital myopathy 7A, and myopathy with lysis of type I myofibrils, is a form of autosomal dominant disease and hyaline body myopathy.
