It is categorized as a type of condition that inherently involves autosomal dominant inheritance mechanisms. The definition of ADHBM is a hyaline body myopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the MYH7 gene located on chromosome 14q11.2.

Isolated sulfite oxidase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease, inherited metabolic disorder, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an inherited metabolic disorder characterized by increased sulfite in the urine with markedly decreased inorganic sulfate excretion, resulting in variable phenotypes ranging from severe early-onset disease to late-onset, milder disease. This disorder has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SUOX gene on chromosome 12q13.2. Additionally, isolated sulfite oxidase deficiency has an exact synonym, sulfocysteinuria.

Oliver McFarlane Syndrome is a type of syndrome, specifically an autosomal recessive disease, that has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by trichomegaly, severe chorioretinal atrophy, and multiple pituitary hormone deficiencies due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in PNPLA6 on chromosome 19p13.2. This syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms including OMCS, eyelashes long mental retardation, long eyelashes-intellectual disability syndrome, and trichomegaly-retina pigmentary degeneration-dwarfism syndrome.

Occipital Horn Syndrome (OHS) is a type of X-linked recessive disease and a metal metabolism disorder. It is characterized by a range of symptoms including hyperelastic and bruisable skin, hernias, bladder diverticula, hyperextensible joints, varicosities, abnormal copper transport, and multiple skeletal abnormalities, all of which are caused by X-linked recessive inheritance of mutations in the ATP7A gene on Xq21.1. This disorder is closely related to Menkes disease. Moreover, OHS is also known by several exact synonyms, including Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome Type 9, Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome Type IX, EDS IX, and X-linked cutis laxa.

NARP syndrome is a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease, which is also characterized by developmental delay, retinitis pigmentosa, dementia, seizures, ataxia, proximal neurogenic muscle weakness, and sensory neuropathy. This disease is caused by a heteroplasmic mutation in the mitochondrial gene MTATP6. It exhibits symptoms including muscle weakness. Moreover, NARP syndrome is exactly synonymous with Neurogenic muscle weakness-ataxia-retinitis pigmentosa syndrome, Neuropathy-ataxia-retinitis pigmentosa syndrome, and neuropathy, ataxia and retinitis pigmentosa.

Codas Syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases and is something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by developmental delay, and anomalies in cerebral, ocular, dental, auricular, and skeletal aspects. This is due to a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LONP1 gene located on chromosome 19p13.3. Codas Syndrome is also exactly known as the cerebral, ocular, dental, auricular, and skeletal syndrome, as well as the cerebro-oculo-dento-auriculo-skeletal syndrome.

Speech language disorder 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, speech disorder, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a speech disorder characterized by severe orofacial dyspraxia resulting in largely incomprehensible speech that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FOXP2 gene on chromosome 7q31.1. Speech language disorder 1 is also known by several exact synonyms, including CAS, articulatory apraxia, childhood apraxia of speech, developmental apraxia of speech, developmental verbal dyspraxia, speech and language disorder with orofacial dyspraxia, and speech-language disorder type 1.

Sensory ataxic neuropathy, dysarthria, and ophthalmoparesis (SANDO) is a type of disease classified under both autosomal recessive diseases and mitochondrial metabolism diseases. It is specifically tied to conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is characterized by mitochondrial dysfunction, which typically manifests in adults as sensory ataxic neuropathy, dysarthria, and progressive external ophthalmoparesis. The disease is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the POLG gene located on chromosome 15q26.1. Additionally, SANDO is known by the exact synonym "autosomal recessive sensory ataxic neuropathy with mitochondrial DNA deletions."

Mitochondrial trifunctional protein deficiency (MTPD), also known as TFP deficiency or TFPD, is an autosomal recessive disease that falls under the category of lipid metabolism disorders. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and presents a phenotype of pigmentary retinopathy. This condition features several clinical manifestations, including cardiomyopathy, metabolic acidosis, liver disease, myopathy, neuropathy, and hypoglycemia. MTPD is defined as a lipid metabolism disorder with abnormal fatty acid oxidation leading to a wide range of clinical manifestations, from severe neonatal symptoms such as cardiomyopathy, hypoglycemia, metabolic acidosis, skeletal myopathy, neuropathy, liver disease, and potential death, to a milder phenotype that includes peripheral polyneuropathy, episodic rhabdomyolysis, and pigmentary retinopathy. The disorder is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in either of the subunits of the mitochondrial trifunctional protein, HADHA or HADHB, located on chromosome 2p23.3.

Histiocytosis lymphadenopathy plus syndrome is a type of syndrome, specifically an autosomal recessive disease, which has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and symptoms including hepatosplenomegaly. This syndrome is characterized by a range of symptoms: histiocytosis, hyperpigmentation, hypertrichosis, hepatosplenomegaly, heart anomalies, hearing loss, hypogonadism, and reduced height. It is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC29A3 gene located on chromosome 10q22.1. Notably, this syndrome encompasses features of four histiocytic disorders previously considered distinct: Faisalabad histiocytosis, sinus histiocytosis with massive lymphadenopathy (SHML), H syndrome, and pigmented hypertrichosis with insulin-dependent diabetes mellitus syndrome.

The syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including Faisalabad histiocytosis, H syndrome, HJCD, PHID, Rosai–Dorfman disease, SHML, cutaneous hyperpigmentation with hypertrichosis, hepatosplenomegaly, heart anomalies, and hypogonadism with or without hearing loss, familial Rosai-Dorfman disease, histiocytosis and lymphadenopathy with or without cutaneous, cardiac, and/or endocrine features, joint contractures and/or deafness, histiocytosis with joint contractures and sensorineural deafness, pigmented hypertrichosis with insulin-dependent diabetes mellitus, and sinus histiocytosis and massive lymphadenopathy.

Psoriasis 7 is a type of psoriasis, which is defined as a psoriasis that has a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 1p that includes IL23R. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, PSORS7.
Psoriasis 4 is a type of psoriasis, which is defined as a psoriasis that has a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 1q21. Moreover, it is exactly synonymous with PSORS4.

Psoriasis 15 is a type of psoriasis and it is also known by its exact synonym PSORS15. It is characterized as a psoriasis defined by pustular psoriasis that originates from a heterozygous mutation in the AP1S3 gene located on chromosome 2q36.1.
Psoriasis 5 is a type of psoriasis, which is defined by a psoriasis that has a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 3q21. Additionally, it has the exact synonym PSORS5.
Psoriasis 3 is a type of psoriasis that has material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 4q. It is also exactly synonymous with PSORS3.
Psoriasis 9 is a type of psoriasis, which is defined as a psoriasis that has a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 4q31-q34. Additionally, Psoriasis 9 has an exact synonym, PSORS9.

Psoriasis 11 is a type of psoriasis and is exactly synonymized with PSORS11. It is defined as a psoriasis that has a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 5q31.1-q33.1, including IL12B.
Psoriasis 1 is a type of psoriasis and has the exact synonym PSORS1. It is defined as a psoriasis that has a material basis in variation in HLA-C on chromosome 6p21.33.
Psoriasis 13 is a type of psoriasis, also known exactly as PSORS13. It is defined as a psoriasis that has its material basis in variation in the TRAF3IP2 gene on chromosome 6q21.

Psoriasis 8 is a type of psoriasis, which is defined as a psoriasis that has a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 16q. This region overlaps one that is associated with inflammatory bowel disease 1 disease. Furthermore, Psoriasis 8 has an exact synonym, PSORS8.
Psoriasis 10 is a type of psoriasis, which is defined as a psoriasis that has a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 18p11.23. Furthermore, it has the exact synonym PSORS10.

Psoriasis 6 is a type of psoriasis that has a definition as a psoriasis with a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 19p13 that includes BSG. Furthermore, Psoriasis 6 has an exact synonym, PSORS6.

Psoriasis 12 is a type of psoriasis and it is exactly synonymous with PSORS12. It is defined as a psoriasis that has a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 20q13, which includes RNF114.

Idiopathic generalized epilepsy 10 is a type of idiopathic generalized epilepsy and has an exact synonym, EIG10. It is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy that has its material basis in variation in the GABRD on chromosome 1p36.33.

Generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 4 is a type of generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus, characterized by a variation in a region on chromosome 2p24. This condition is also precisely known by several synonyms, including GEFS+4, GEFSP4, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 4, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 4, and generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 4.

Generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 2 is a type of generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus that is characterized by a genetic condition. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SCN1A gene located on chromosome 2q24.3. This condition is also precisely known by several synonyms, including GEFS+2, GEFSP2, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 2, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 2, and generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 2.

Generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 7, a type of generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus, is defined as a generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in SCN9A on chromosome 2q24.3. It is exactly synonymous with GEFS+7, GEFSP7, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 7, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 7, and generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 7.

Generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 10 is a particular type of generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus, defined as a generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the HCN1 gene on chromosome 5p12. This condition is precisely synonymous with several terms: GEFS+10, GEFSP10, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 10, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 10, and generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 10, all referring to the same medical condition.

Familial febrile seizures, a type of brain disease, are characterized by seizures during childhood associated with febrile episodes without any evidence of intracranial infection or defined pathologic or traumatic cause, and they exhibit a familial pattern of inheritance. This condition is also exactly synonymous with FEB and familial febrile convulsions.

Familial Febrile Seizures 8 is a type of Familial Febrile Seizures, which is defined as a Familial Febrile Seizures that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GABRG2 gene on chromosome 5q34. It also has the exact synonyms FEB8 and Familial Febrile Convulsions 8.

Generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 8 is a specific type of generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus, characterized by a genetic variation located on chromosome 6q16.3-q22.31. It is known by several exact synonyms including GEFS+8, GEFSP8, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 8, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 8, and generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 8.

Generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 6 is a type of generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus, defined as a generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus that has a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 8p23-p21. It has several exact synonyms including GEFS+6, GEFSP6, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 6, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 6, and generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 6.

Generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 9 (GEFS+9) is a type of generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus, which is defined as a generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the STX1B gene located on chromosome 16p11.2. This condition is also precisely known by several other synonyms, including GEFSP9, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 9, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 9, and generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 9.

Generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 1 is a specific type of generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus. It is defined as a generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SCN1B gene on chromosome 19q13.11. This condition is also precisely known by several exact synonyms including GEFS+1, GEFSP1, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus 1, generalised epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 1, and generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus type 1.

Familial Febrile Seizures 9 is a type of familial febrile seizures, which is defined as a familial febrile seizures that has a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 3p24.2-p23. It is also exactly synonymous with FEB9 and Familial Febrile Convulsions 9.

Familial Febrile Seizures 10 is a type of familial febrile seizures and it is defined as a familial febrile seizures that has its material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 3q26.2-q26.33. It has exact synonyms, which include FEB10 and familial febrile convulsions 10.

Familial Febrile Seizures 4 is a type of Familial Febrile Seizures defined by a familial febrile seizure that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ADGRV1 gene on chromosome 5q14.3. It is exactly synonymous with FEB4 and Familial Febrile Convulsions 4.

Familial febrile seizures 5 is a type of familial febrile seizures, defined as a familial febrile seizures that has its material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 6q22-q24. It is exactly synonymous with FEB5 and familial febrile convulsions 5.

Familial Febrile Seizures 1 is a type of familial febrile seizures defined as a familial febrile seizures that has a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 8q13-q21. It is exactly synonymous with FEB1 and familial febrile convulsions 1.

Familial febrile seizures 11 is a specific type of familial febrile seizures, which is characterized by having a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the CPA6 gene located on chromosome 8p13.2. It is exactly synonymous with both FEB11 and familial febrile convulsions 11.

Familial Febrile Seizures 6 is a type of familial febrile seizures that is defined by a familial febrile seizures which has a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 18p11.2. It is exactly synonymous with FEB6 and Familial Febrile Convulsions 6.

Familial Febrile Seizures 2 is a specific type of Familial Febrile Seizures. It is defined as a familial febrile seizures that has its material basis in a variation in a region on chromosome 19p13.3. Furthermore, Familial Febrile Seizures 2 is exactly synonymous with FEB2 and Familial Febrile Convulsions 2.

Familial febrile seizures 7 is a type of familial febrile seizures and is defined as a familial febrile seizures that has its material basis in heterozygous mutation. It is exactly synonymous with FEB7 and familial febrile convulsions 7.

Idiopathic generalized epilepsy 11 is a type of idiopathic generalized epilepsy and has an exact synonym EIG11. It is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CLCN2 gene located on chromosome 3q27.1.

Idiopathic generalized epilepsy 12 is a type of idiopathic generalized epilepsy and is exactly synonymous with EIG12. It is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SLC2A1 on chromosome 1p34.2.

Idiopathic Generalized Epilepsy 13 is a type of Idiopathic Generalized Epilepsy, which is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GABRA1 on chromosome 5q34. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with EIG13.

Idiopathic Generalized Epilepsy 14 (EIG14) is a type of idiopathic generalized epilepsy. It is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SLC12A5 gene located on chromosome 20q13.12.

Idiopathic generalized epilepsy 15 is a type of idiopathic generalized epilepsy and has the exact synonym EIG15. It is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RORB on chromosome 9q21.13.
Idiopathic Generalized Epilepsy 2 (EIG2) is a type of idiopathic generalized epilepsy characterized by having its material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 14q23.

Idiopathic Generalized Epilepsy 3 is a type of Idiopathic Generalized Epilepsy, which is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy that has its material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 9q32-q33. Additionally, Idiopathic Generalized Epilepsy 3 is exactly synonymous with EIG3.

Idiopathic Generalized Epilepsy 4 is a type of Idiopathic Generalized Epilepsy and has an exact synonym, EIG4. It is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy that has its material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 10q25-q26.

Idiopathic Generalized Epilepsy 5 is a type of idiopathic generalized epilepsy, which is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy that has its material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 10p11.22. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with EIG5.

Idiopathic Generalized Epilepsy 7 (EIG7) is a type of idiopathic generalized epilepsy. It is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy that has its material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 15q14.

Idiopathic generalized epilepsy 8 is a type of idiopathic generalized epilepsy, which is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CASR on chromosome 3q13.3-q21.1. Additionally, idiopathic generalized epilepsy 8 is exactly synonymous with EIG8.

Idiopathic Generalized Epilepsy 9 is a type of Idiopathic Generalized Epilepsy and has an exact synonym EIG9. It is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CACNB4 gene located on chromosome 2q23.3.

Juvenile absence epilepsy 1 is a type of juvenile absence epilepsy characterized by a juvenile absence epilepsy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in EFHC1 on 6p12.2. It is also exactly synonymous with EJA1 and JAE1.

Juvenile myoclonic epilepsy 10 is a type of juvenile myoclonic epilepsy and also falls under a category of conditions that begin in young adulthood. It is specifically defined as a juvenile myoclonic epilepsy that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the ICK gene located on chromosome 6p12.1. Additionally, juvenile myoclonic epilepsy 10 is exactly synonymous with EJM10.

Juvenile myoclonic epilepsy 3 (JME3) is a specific type of juvenile myoclonic epilepsy, which begins in young adulthood. It is defined as a juvenile myoclonic epilepsy that has its material basis in a variation in a region on chromosome 6p21. Furthermore, JME3 is exactly synonymous with EJM3.

Juvenile myoclonic epilepsy 4 (EJM4) is a type of juvenile myoclonic epilepsy and also categorized as a type that typically begins during young adult onset. This specific condition is defined as a juvenile myoclonic epilepsy that has its material basis in a variation in a region on chromosome 5q12-q14.

Juvenile myoclonic epilepsy 9 is a type of juvenile myoclonic epilepsy that begins during young adult onset. It is defined as a juvenile myoclonic epilepsy that has a material basis in heterozygous variation in a region on chromosome 2q33-q36. Additionally, juvenile myoclonic epilepsy 9 is exactly synonymous with EJM9.

Pyridoxamine 5 phosphate oxidase deficiency is a type of vitamin metabolic disorder, specifically characterized by a vitamin B6 deficiency resulting in neonatal-onset of severe seizures. These seizures can be controlled with pyridoxal 5'-phosphate treatment, and the condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in PNPO on 17q21.32. It is also known by several exact synonyms including PNPO deficiency, PNPO-related neonatal epileptic encephalopathy, pyridoxal 5'-phosphate-dependent epilepsy, pyridoxal phosphate-dependent seizures, pyridoxal phosphate-responsive seizures, pyridoxamine 5'-oxidase deficiency, and pyridoxamine 5-prime-phosphate oxidase deficiency.

Combined saposin deficiency is a type of sphingolipidosis and is also known as something that at least has the symptom of hepatosplenomegaly. It is characterized by the absence of expression of both isoforms of PSAP (SAP1 and SAP2), leading to hepatosplenomegaly and severe neurological disease. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in PSAP on chromosome 10q22.1. Furthermore, combined saposin deficiency is exactly synonymous with PSAPD, combined SAP deficiency, and encephalopathy due to prosaposin deficiency.

Intellectual disability severe speech delay mild dysmorphism syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of syndromic intellectual disability. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and also exhibits a phenotype of neurodevelopmental delay. Specifically, it is defined as a syndromic intellectual disability characterized by global developmental delay with moderate to severe speech delay, dysmorphic craniofacial features, and gross motor skill delays that particularly affects expressive speech, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FOXP1 gene on chromosome 3p13. This syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: FOXP1 Haploinsufficiency, FOXP1 syndrome, FOXP1-Related Neurodevelopmental Disorder, and Mental retardation with language impairment and with or without autistic features.

Pitt Hopkins like syndrome 2 (PTHSL2) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a syndromic intellectual disability that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by neurodevelopmental delay among other features. Specifically, it is defined as a syndromic intellectual disability marked by developmental delay and intellectual disability, with many patients also displaying infantile hypotonia and autistic features, resulting from compound heterozygous or homozygous mutations in the NRXN1 gene on chromosome 2p16.3.

Early onset myopathy areflexia respiratory distress dysphagia syndrome, also known by its exact synonyms EMARDD, Myopathy, areflexia, respiratory distress, and dysphagia, early-onset, and congenital myopathy 10A, is a type of autosomal recessive disease, congenital myopathy, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and has symptoms including muscle weakness. This syndrome is characterized by a congenital myopathy marked by proximal and generalized muscle weakness, respiratory difficulties, joint contractures, and scoliosis, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MEGF10 gene located on chromosome 5q23.2.

Congenital leptin deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease, physical disorder, and syndrome that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and is based on some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by severe early-onset obesity, hyperphagia, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, and neuroendocrine and metabolic dysfunction that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in LEP on chromosome 7q32.1. Furthermore, congenital leptin deficiency is exactly synonymous with LEPD, leptin deficiency or dysfunction, morbid obesity, and obesity due to congenital leptin deficiency.

Myopathy with extrapyramidal signs (MPXPS), also known as proximal myopathy with extrapyramidal signs, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of myopathy. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance and typically manifests symptoms such as muscle weakness. This particular myopathy is defined by an early childhood onset of proximal muscle weakness, alongside the development of progressive extrapyramidal motor signs in most patients, and learning disabilities. These manifestations have their material basis in either compound heterozygous or homozygous mutations in the MICU1 gene located on chromosome 10q22.1.

Craniofacial deafness hand syndrome (CDHS), also known exactly as Sommer-Young-Wee-Frye syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome. It is characterized by a flat facial profile, hypertelorism, a hypoplastic nose with slit-like nares, and sensorineural hearing loss. This syndrome has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PAX3 gene on chromosome 2q36.1, which is a form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Jackson Weiss Syndrome is a type of syndrome that is autosomal recessive, meaning it at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by craniosynostosis, midfacial hypoplasia, and foot malformations due to a heterozygous mutation in the FGFR2 gene on chromosome 10q26.13. Additionally, Jackson Weiss Syndrome has exact synonyms, including JWS and craniosynostosis-midfacial hypoplasia-foot abnormalities syndrome.

Isolated elevated serum creatine phosphokinase levels, also known exactly as elevated serum CPK, idiopathic hyperCKemia, and isolated hyperCKemia, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and an inherited metabolic disorder. This condition is characterized by elevated serum creatine kinase levels in the absence of muscle weakness or other symptoms. It has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, and in some cases, it is due to a heterozygous mutation in the CAV3 gene on chromosome 3p25.3.

Vohwinkel syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome, which fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by a syndrome that includes severe, honeycomb-patterned palmoplantar keratosis, constrictions on the fingers and toes leading to autoamputation, and mild to moderate congenital sensorineural hearing loss. This syndrome is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the GJB2 gene located on chromosome 13q12.11. Vohwinkel syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including KHM, Mutilating keratoderma plus deafness, PPK mutilans and deafness, VOWNKL, congenital deafness with keratopachydermia and constrictions of fingers and toes, keratoderma hereditarium mutilans, and mutilating keratoderma of Vohwinkel.

Dominant optic atrophy plus syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome, which fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by a variety of symptoms including ataxia, hyperreflexia, muscle cramp, and loss of vision. Additionally, it features sensorineural hearing loss as a disease characteristic. The syndrome is defined as one characterized by visual loss and sensorineural hearing loss, with an onset in childhood. It is associated with other symptoms such as progressive external ophthalmoplegia, muscle cramps, hyperreflexia, and ataxia, all of which have their material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the OPA1 gene on chromosome 3q29. Dominant optic atrophy plus syndrome is also exactly synonymous with DOA+ and is known as optic atrophy with or without deafness, ophthalmoplegia, myopathy, ataxia, and neuropathy.

Primary failure of tooth eruption is a type of tooth disease, autosomal dominant disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by incomplete tooth eruption despite the presence of a clear eruption pathway and has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the PTHR1 gene on chromosome 3p21.31. Primary failure of tooth eruption has exact synonyms including PFE, dental noneruption, familial posterior openbite malocclusion, nonsyndromic primary failure of eruption, primary retention of teeth, and unerupted second primary molar.

Dermatopathia pigmentosa reticularis (DPR) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, ectodermal dysplasia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an ectodermal dysplasia characterized by reticulate hyperpigmentation, noncicatricial alopecia, and onychodystrophy, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KRT14 gene on chromosome 17q21.2.

Lateral meningocele syndrome, also exactly synonymous with Lehman syndrome, is a type of syndrome that is categorized as an autosomal dominant disease. It is recognized for having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The syndrome is defined by facial anomalies, hyperextensibility, hypotonia, and neurologic dysfunction related to meningocele, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NOTCH3 gene located on chromosome 19p13.12.

Myeloproliferative disorder with eosinophilia is a type of myeloproliferative neoplasm and has another name, chronic myeloproliferative disorder with eosinophilia. It is defined as a myeloproliferative neoplasm characterized by chronic proliferation of myeloid cells and eosinophilia in the peripheral blood and bone marrow. This disorder has a material basis in a fusion of the ETV6 and PDGFRB genes, which is formed by a translocation from chromosome 12 to chromosome 5q32.

Transient Bullous Dermolysis of the Newborn (TBDN) is categorized as a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the category of epidermolysis bullosa dystrophica. Furthermore, it is identified as a condition that essentially has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. TBDN is defined as an epidermolysis bullosa dystrophica characterized by generalized blistering at birth, which generally regresses by 6 to 24 months of age, and has its material basis in heterozygous, compound heterozygous, or homozygous mutation in the COL7A1 gene located on chromosome 3p21.31. In addition, TBDN is precisely synonymous with DEB (Dystrophic Epidermolysis Bullosa) and DEB-BDN (Dystrophic Epidermolysis Bullosa, Bullous Dermolysis of the Newborn).

Epidermolysis bullosa simplex with mottled pigmentation (EBSMP) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of epidermolysis bullosa simplex. It is characterized by generalized blistering along with mottled hyper- and hypopigmentation of the skin, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the KRT5 gene located on chromosome 12q13.13. This condition falls under the broader category of disorders that have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. EBSMP is also exactly synonymous with Epidermolysis bullosa simplex-MP and speckled hyperpigmentation with punctate palmoplantar keratoses and childhood blistering, indicating these terminologies refer to the same condition.

Epidermolysis bullosa with congenital localized absence of skin and deformity of nails is a type of physical disorder that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases, specifically it is classified as an autosomal dominant dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa. This condition is characterized by the fact that it has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance, and it is also understood that the disease has its basis in some form of abnormality related to prenatal development or birth. Furthermore, it is defined as an autosomal dominant dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa that is characterized by severe blistering of skin and mucous membranes, congenital absence of skin on the lower extremities, and congenital absence or deformity of nails, which stems from a heterozygous mutation in the COL7A1 gene on chromosome 3p21.31. Additionally, this condition is known by its exact synonyms: EBD, Bart type, and epidermolysis bullosa dystrophica, Bart type.

Multiple epiphyseal dysplasia with myopia and deafness is a type of autosomal dominant disease, a syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by typically mild epiphyseal dysplasia, progressive myopia, retinal thinning, crenated cataracts, conductive deafness, and brachydactyly that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the COL2A1 gene on chromosome 12q13.11. This condition is also known by its exact synonyms: EDMMD, multiple epiphyseal dysplasia, Beighton type, and multiple epiphyseal dysplasia-myopia-deafness syndrome.

Hereditary desmoid disease is a type of syndrome, autosomal genetic disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by the extraintestinal manifestation of familial adenomatous polyposis, which, in some cases, is caused by extreme 3' mutation in APC on 5q22.2. Moreover, hereditary desmoid disease has the exact synonyms FIF and familial infiltrative fibromatosis.

Laurin Sandrow Syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and dysostosis, which is based on autosomal dominant inheritance. It affects specific locations such as the foot and hand. The syndrome is characterized by polysyndactyly of hands and/or feet, mirror-image duplication of the feet, nasal defects, and the loss of identity between fibula and tibia. This condition results from heterozygous inheritance of small (less than 80kb) duplications in a SHH regulatory element located in intron 5 of the LMBR1 gene on chromosome 7q36.3. Laurin Sandrow Syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including MIPduplication of fibula and ulna with absence of tibia and radius, Sandrow Syndrome, TMIP, miccor hands and feet with nasal defects, mirror hands and feets-nasal defects syndrome, mirror-image polydactyly, and tetramelic mirror-image polydactyly.

D 2 hydroxyglutaric aciduria 1 is a type of D 2 hydroxyglutaric aciduria and is also classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, which fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific condition, D 2 hydroxyglutaric aciduria 1, is defined as a D-2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the D2HGDH gene located on chromosome 2q37.3. Additionally, D 2 hydroxyglutaric aciduria 1 is exactly synonymous with D2HGA1.

D-2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria 2, which is also exactly synonymous with D2HGA2, is a specific type of D-2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria. It is categorized as a type of autosomal dominant disease and is defined by having a material basis in at least some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, D-2-hydroxyglutaric aciduria 2 is characterized by a heterozygous mutation in the IDH2 gene located on chromosome 15q26.1.

Arthrogryposis renal dysfunction and cholestasis 1 (ARCS1) is a type of ARC syndrome and also a type of condition that has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an arthrogryposis, renal dysfunction, and cholestasis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in VPS33B on 15q26.1.

Arthrogryposis renal dysfunction and cholestasis 2 (ARCS2) is a type of ARC syndrome and also a type of condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an arthrogryposis, renal dysfunction, and cholestasis that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in VIPAS39 on chromosome 14q24.3.

Hydrolethalus syndrome 1 is a type of Hydrolethalus syndrome and has an exact synonym, HLS1. It is defined as a Hydrolethalus syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the HYLS1 gene on chromosome 11q24.2.

Hydrolethalus Syndrome 2 is a type of Hydrolethalus Syndrome, which is defined as a Hydrolethalus Syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KIF7 gene on chromosome 15q26.1. It is also precisely known as HLS2.

Adermatoglyphia is a type of autosomal dominant and skin disease that primarily affects the areas where the foot and hand intersect, specifically lacking epidermal ridges on the fingers, toes, palms, and soles. This condition is characterized by a heterozygous mutation in the SMARCAD1 gene on chromosome 4q22.3. It has several exact synonyms, including ADERM, ADG, Absence of fingerprints, Congenital absence of fingerprints, Immigration delay disease, and Isolated congenital adermatoglyphia.

Floating Harbor Syndrome (FLHS) is a syndrome that is classified as an autosomal dominant disease and has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by several distinctive features: growth retardation, proportionate short stature, delayed bone age, delayed speech development, and specific facial features including a triangular shape, deep-set eyes, long eyelashes, bulbous nose, wide columella, short philtrum, and thin lips. The cause of Floating Harbor Syndrome is a heterozygous mutation in the SRCAP gene located on chromosome 16p11.2.

Large congenital melanocytic nevus is recognized as a type of physical disorder, skin disease, and something that at least has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a skin disease characterized by the presence at birth of a pigmented skin lesion composed of melanocytes of more than 20 cm in projected adult diameter, which has its material basis in a somatic mutation in the NRAS gene on chromosome 11p15.5. Furthermore, it is synonymously known as Congenital pigmented nevus, GMN, Giant congenital melanocytic nevus, Giant pigmented hairy nevus, and LCMN.

Hypotrichosis lymphedema telangiectasia renal defect syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome, which is something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by the onset in childhood of progressive hypotrichosis, lymphedema, telangiectasia, and renal defects due to a heterozygous mutation in the SOX18 gene on chromosome 20q13.33. This syndrome is also exactly known as HLT-renal defect syndrome, HLTRS, glomerulonephritis with sparse hair and telangiectases, hypotrichosis-lymphedema-telangiectasia-membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis syndrome, and telangiectatic membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis.

Hypotrichosis lymphedema telangiectasia syndrome (HLTS) is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that is fundamentally rooted in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by the onset at birth or early childhood of progressive hypotrichosis, lymphedema, and telangiectasia due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SOX18 gene on chromosome 20q13.33.

Hawkinsinuria is a type of autosomal dominant disease, amino acid metabolic disorder, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by a defect in tyrosine metabolism with transient metabolic acidosis and tyrosinemia that improves with a phenylalanine and tyrosine restricted diet. Additionally, it involves the presence of the hawkinsin metabolite in the urine throughout life, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the HPD gene on chromosome 12q24.31. Hawkinsinuria is also known by its exact synonyms: 4-Alpha-hydroxyphenylpyruvate hydroxylase deficiency, 4-HPPD deficiency, and 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvic acid dioxygenase deficiency.

Heinz body anemia is a type of autosomal dominant disease that falls under the category of congenital nonspherocytic hemolytic anemias, specifically characterized by being a condition with a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a congenital nonspherocytic hemolytic anemia of Dacie type I, where Heinz bodies are observed in erythrocytes following a splenectomy. This condition is caused by heterozygous mutations in the HBA1, HBA2, or HBB genes located on chromosomes 11p15.4, 16p13.3, and 16p13.3, respectively.

Alzheimer's disease 9 is a type of Alzheimer's disease and an autosomal dominant disease, indicating it is a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as an Alzheimer's disease that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ABCA7 gene on chromosome 19p13.3. Furthermore, Alzheimer's disease 9 has exact synonyms, including AD9 and Alzheimer's disease 9, late onset.

Benign familial hematuria is a type of disease that is classified both as an autosomal dominant disease and a urinary system disease, specifically one that has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is characterized by the presence of blood in the urine, thinning of the glomerular basement membrane, and normal renal function, attributing its cause to heterozygous mutations in either the COL4A3 gene or the COL4A4 gene located on chromosome 2q36.3. Additionally, benign familial hematuria is also known by its exact synonyms: BFH, TMN, thin basement membrane nephropathy, and thin membrane nephropathy.

Familial hepatic adenoma is a type of autosomal recessive disease and hepatocellular adenoma, related to something that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a hepatocellular adenoma characterized by highly vascularized liver adenomas, which results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the HNF1A gene located on chromosome 12q24.31. Additionally, familial hepatic adenoma is exactly synonymous with familial liver cell adenomas.

Beukes hip dysplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease, osteoarthritis, and something that necessarily has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an osteoarthritis characterized by bilateral dysmorphism of the proximal femur, resulting in severe progressive degenerative osteoarthritis of the hip joint in early adulthood. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in UFSP2 on chromosome 4q35.1. Beukes hip dysplasia is also known by its exact synonyms: BFHD, Beukes familial hip dysplasia, Beukes type hip dysplasia, Cilliers-Beighton syndrome, and Premature degenerative osteoarthropathy of the hip.

Cholesterol ester transfer protein deficiency is a type of lipid metabolism disorder, which is characterized by elevated levels of alpha-lipoprotein in the blood. It is also known by its exact synonyms: CEPT deficiency and familial hyperalphalipoproteinemia.

Hyperalphalipoproteinemia 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, a type of cholesterol ester transfer protein deficiency, and a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a cholesterol-ester transfer protein deficiency characterized by elevated levels of alpha-lipoprotein in the blood, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the CETP gene located on chromosome 16q13. Additionally, hyperalphalipoproteinemia 1 is precisely synonymous with HALP1.

Apolipoprotein C III deficiency is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also a type of cholesterol ester transfer protein deficiency. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this deficiency is defined as a cholesterol-ester transfer protein deficiency characterized by elevated levels of alpha-lipoprotein in the blood, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the APOC3 gene located on chromosome 11q23.3. Additionally, apolipoprotein C III deficiency is exactly synonymous with HALP2 and hyperalphalipoproteinemia 2.

Isolated hyperchlorhidrosis is a type of skin disease and a specific form of an autosomal recessive disease that also falls under the broader category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by an excessive loss of salt in sweat, leading to low levels of salt in the blood without the presence of other symptoms. This condition is the result of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CA12 gene located on chromosome 15q22.2. Moreover, isolated hyperchlorhidrosis is precisely referred to by the exact synonyms HYCHL and carbonic anhydrase XII deficiency.

Familial progressive hyperpigmentation with or without hypopigmentation (FPHH), also known precisely as MUH or melanosis universalis hereditaria, is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, a skin disease, and specifically as something that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This skin disease is characterized by progressive, diffuse hyperpigmentation of variable intensity, occasionally accompanied by cafe-au-lait macules and larger hypopigmented ash-leaf macules, which originates from a heterozygous mutation in the KITLG gene on chromosome 12q21.32.

Selective pituitary thyroid hormone resistance is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of hyperthyroidism that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by mild to moderate hyperthyroidism, impaired pituitary response to thyroid hormone, elevated levels of thyroid hormone, and is associated with thyrotoxic features due to a heterozygous mutation in the THRB gene located on chromosome 3p24.2. This condition is precisely known by several exact synonyms, including PRTH, familial hyperthyroidism due to inappropriate thyrotropin secretion, pituitary resistance to thyroid hormone, and selective pituitary resistance to thyroid hormone.

Fetal akinesia deformation sequence syndrome (FADS) is a type of monogenic disease, syndrome, and something that has its basis in some gene. It is characterized by decreased fetal movements, intrauterine growth restriction, joint contractures, and developmental anomalies, including lung hypoplasia, cleft palate, and cryptorchidism. This often has a material basis in a mutation in a gene associated with the neuromuscular junction. FADS is also known by several exact synonyms, including Pena-Shokeir syndrome type 1, arthrogryposis multiplex congenita-pulmonary hypoplasia syndrome, fetal akinesia sequence, foetal akinesia deformation sequence syndrome, and foetal akinesia sequence.

Fetal akinesia deformation sequence syndrome 3 (FADS3) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a form of fetal akinesia deformation sequence syndrome. It is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. The syndrome is defined by a fetal akinesia deformation sequence that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DOK7 gene located on chromosome 4p16.3.

Fetal akinesia deformation sequence syndrome 1 (FADS1) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of fetal akinesia deformation sequence syndrome, characterized by material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a fetal akinesia deformation sequence that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MUSK gene on chromosome 9q31.3.

Fetal Akinesia Deformation Sequence Syndrome 2 (FADS2) is a specific type of Fetal Akinesia Deformation Sequence Syndrome and a form of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that, at a minimum, has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. FADS2 is defined as a fetal akinesia deformation sequence that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RAPSN gene located on chromosome 11p11.2.

Fetal akinesia deformation sequence syndrome 4 (FADS4) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is also categorized under fetal akinesia deformation sequence syndrome. This particular syndrome is defined as a fetal akinesia deformation sequence that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NUP88 gene located on chromosome 17p13.2. It is also recognized as a condition that arises from something with at least a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Solitary Median Maxillary Central Incisor (SMMCI), also known as fused incisors, single central maxillary incisor, single median maxillary central incisor, or single upper central incisor, is a type of autosomal dominant and tooth disease. It is characterized by a single deciduous and permanent maxillary central incisor that may be isolated or occur with a range of other systemic anomalies. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SHH gene located on chromosome 7q36.3. It is a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

Ivic syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases and is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined by a combination of features including radial ray defect of varying severity, mixed congenital hearing loss, mild thrombocytopenia, and external ophthalmoplegia. The genetic basis of Ivic syndrome is linked to a heterozygous mutation in the SALL4 gene located on chromosome 20q13.2. Known by several exact synonyms, Ivic syndrome is also referred to as Instituto Venezolano de Investigaciones Cientificas syndrome, OORS, Oculootoradial syndrome, oculo-oto-radial syndrome, and includes the features of radial ray defects, hearing impairment, external ophthalmoplegia, and thrombocytopenia.

Ischiocoxopodopatellar syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and dysostosis, which is a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by hypoplasia or aplasia of the patellas and various anomalies of the pelvis and feet, with this condition having a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TBX4 gene on chromosome 17q23.2. This syndrome is also known by various exact synonyms, including SPS, Scott-Taor syndrome, congenital coxa vara, patella aplasia and tarsal synostosis, coxo-podo-patellar syndrome, coxopodipatellar syndrome, ischiocoxopodopatellar syndrome with or without pulmonary arterial hypertension, ischiopatellar dysplasia, patella aplasia, coxa vara, and tarsal synostosis, and small patella syndrome.

Autosomal dominant keratitis is a type of disease that is autosomal dominant and a form of keratitis. It is defined as a keratitis characterized by corneal opacification and vascularization, and foveal hypoplasia, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PAX6 gene on chromosome 11p13. This condition is also precisely known as hereditary keratitis. Additionally, it is a type of condition that necessarily involves some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Inclusion Body Myopathy with Early Onset Paget Disease of Bone with or without Frontotemporal Dementia 2 (IBMPFD2), also known exactly as MSP2 or Multisystem Proteinopathy 2, is categorized as a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is specifically identified as a type of Inclusion Body Myopathy with Paget Disease of Bone and Frontotemporal Dementia and falls under a broader category that encompasses conditions with a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. IBMPFD2 is defined as an Inclusion Body Myopathy with Paget Disease of Bone and Frontotemporal Dementia that results from a heterozygous mutation in the HNRPA2B1 gene located on chromosome 7p15.2.

Inclusion body myopathy with early onset Paget disease of bone with or without frontotemporal dementia 1 (IBMPFD1), also known exactly as MSP1 and multisystem proteinopathy 1, is a type of both autosomal dominant disease and inclusion body myopathy with Paget disease of bone and frontotemporal dementia. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of IBMPFD1 is an inclusion body myopathy with Paget disease of bone and frontotemporal dementia that results from a heterozygous mutation in the VCP gene on chromosome 9p13.3.

Inclusion body myopathy with early onset Paget disease of bone with or without frontotemporal dementia 3 (IBMPFD3), also known precisely as multisystem proteinopathy 3 (MSP3), is characterized as a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is categorized under inclusion body myopathy with Paget disease of bone and frontotemporal dementia, indicating that it essentially involves a condition that, at the very least, has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of IBMPFD3 emphasizes it as an inclusion body myopathy with Paget disease of bone and frontotemporal dementia that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the HNRNPA1 gene on chromosome 12q13.13.

Familial isolated hypoparathyroidism is a type of hypoparathyroidism. It is defined as a hypoparathyroidism that has its material basis in mutation in the PTH gene on chromosome 6p24.2 or in the GCM2 gene on chromosome 11p15.3. Familial isolated hypoparathyroidism also has an exact synonym, FIH.

X-linked hypoparathyroidism is a type of hypoparathyroidism, which is also classified under X-linked monogenic diseases and is considered a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of X-linked inheritance. It is specifically defined as a form of hypoparathyroidism that has its material basis in a mutation in a region on chromosome Xq27.1, which seems to alter the expression of SOX3. Furthermore, X-linked hypoparathyroidism is exactly synonymous with HYPX and agenesis of parathyroid glands.

Mucopolysaccharidosis IH/S is a type of mucopolysaccharidosis I and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by an intermediate severity of symptoms, including short stature, corneal clouding, joint stiffening, umbilical hernia, dysostosis multiplex, hepatosplenomegaly, and little to no intellectual dysfunction. These symptoms arise due to its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IDUA gene on chromosome 4p16.3. Additionally, mucopolysaccharidosis IH/S is associated with autosomal recessive inheritance, and its symptoms notably include hepatosplenomegaly, cloudy cornea, and short stature. The disease also features umbilical hernia. Moreover, mucopolysaccharidosis IH/S is also known by its exact synonyms MPS1H/S, MPSIH/S, and Mucopolysaccharidosis type 1H/S.

Mucopolysaccharidosis IH is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a specific form of mucopolysaccharidosis I, characterized by its basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is associated with several phenotypes including coarse facial features and cognitive impairment, as well as symptoms such as hepatosplenomegaly. It is defined as a severe mucopolysaccharidosis I phenotype that involves dysostosis multiplex, cognitive impairment, heart disease, respiratory problems, corneal clouding, hepatosplenomegaly, coarse facies, and reduced life expectancy. This condition results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IDUA gene on chromosome 4p16.3. Mucopolysaccharidosis IH is also known by several exact synonyms, including Dysostosis multiplex syndrome, Hurler disease MPS type 1H, Hurler-Pfaundler syndrome, L-iduronidase deficiency, Hurler type, MPS1-H, Mucopolysaccharidosis type I severe form, dysostosis multiplex, and gargoylism.

Mucopolysaccharidosis IVA, also known exactly as GALNS deficiency, MPS IVA, MPS4A, Morquio A disease, and Morquio syndrome A, is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease and mucopolysaccharidosis IV. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it involves the intracellular accumulation of keratan sulfate and chondroitin-6-sulfate, leading to manifestations such as short stature, skeletal dysplasia, dental anomalies, and corneal clouding. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GALNS gene located on chromosome 16q24.3.

Mucopolysaccharidosis type IVB is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a specific form of mucopolysaccharidosis IV. It is characterized by skeletal dysplasia, corneal clouding, and increased urinary keratan sulfate excretion, which is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GLB1 gene on chromosome 3p22.3. This condition is synonymous with MPS IVB, MPS4B, Morquio disease type B, Morquio syndrome B, beta-D-galactosidase deficiency, and mucopolysaccharidosis type IVB (Morquio), indicating the various ways it can be referred to in medical literature and discussions.

Mucopolysaccharidosis type IIIC is a subtype of both mucopolysaccharidosis III and autosomal recessive diseases. It specifically arises from a material basis that involves autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as a mucopolysaccharidosis III that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the HGSNAT gene located on chromosome 8p11.2-p11.1. It is known by several exact synonyms, including Acetyl-CoA alpha-glucosaminide acetyltransferase deficiency, HGSNAT deficiency, Heparan-alpha-glucosaminide N-acetyltransferase deficiency, MPS3C, MPSIIIC, Mucopolysaccharidosis type 3C, Sanfilippo syndrome type C, and mucopolysaccharidosis type IIIC (Sanfilippo C).

Mucopolysaccharidosis type IIIB is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the category of mucopolysaccharidosis III. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, mucopolysaccharidosis type IIIB is defined by neurodegeneration, behavioral problems, mild skeletal changes, and a shortened lifespan, due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NAGLU gene on chromosome 17q21.2. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms including MPS3B, MPSIIIB, Mucopoly-saccharidosis type 3B, Mucopolysaccharidosis type 3B, N-acetyl-alpha-glucosaminidase deficiency, NAGLU deficiency, Sanfilippo syndrome type B, and mucopolysaccharidosis type IIIB (Sanfilippo B).

Mucopolysaccharidosis type IIIA is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of mucopolysaccharidosis III. It is characterized by a severe clinical manifestation and an earlier age of onset compared to other forms of mucopolysaccharidosis III, with its material basis being homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SGSH gene on chromosome 17q25.3. Furthermore, mucopolysaccharidosis type IIIA is recognized by several exact synonyms including MPS3A, MPSIIIA, Sanfilippo syndrome type A, heparan sulfamidase deficiency, mucopolysaccharidosis III-A, mucopolysaccharidosis type 3A, and mucopolysaccharidosis type IIIA (Sanfilippo A), indicating the diverse nomenclature used to refer to this condition.

Congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type I is a specific form of congenital dyserythropoietic anemia and is categorized under diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital dyserythropoietic anemia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, presenting with macrocytic anemia, ineffective erythropoiesis, and secondary hemochromatosis. This condition is also precisely known by several synonyms: CDA I, CDA type 1, CDA type I, Congenital dyserythropoietic anaemia type 1, Congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type 1, and congenital dyserythropoietic anaemia type I.

Congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type Ib is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is also classified under congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type I. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and involves some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type Ib is defined as a congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type I that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the C15orf41 gene located on chromosome 15q14. Additionally, congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type Ib is exactly synonymous with CDA, type Ib, and CDAN1B.

Congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type IA (CDA Ia), also precisely known as CDAN1A, is a form of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type I. This condition is characterized by its origin from a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and has its roots in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, CDA Ia is defined by a congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type I that develops due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CDAN1 gene located on chromosome 15q15.2.

Congenital Dyserythropoietic Anemia Type III is a specific type of Congenital Dyserythropoietic Anemia, which falls under the broader category of diseases that originate from abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. This condition is characterized by a congenital dyserythropoietic anemia marked by nonprogressive mild to moderate anemia, macrocytosis in the peripheral blood, and the presence of giant multinucleated erythroblasts. The material basis of this anemia is a heterozygous mutation within the 11 cM interval on chromosome 15q21-q25. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including CDA III, CDA Type 3, CDA Type III, CDAN3, Congenital Dyserythropoietic Anaemia Type 3, Congenital Dyserythropoietic Anemia Type 3, Anemia with Multinucleated Erythroblasts, Anaemia with Multinucleated Erythroblasts, Congenital Dyserythropoietic Anaemia Type III, and Hereditary Benign Erythroreticulosis.

Congenital Dyserythropoietic Anemia Type IV is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the broader category of Congenital Dyserythropoietic Anemia. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is associated with abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. The disease is defined by a congenital dyserythropoietic anemia marked by ineffective erythropoiesis and hemolysis, leading to anemia and abnormal erythroblast morphology, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the KLF1 gene on chromosome 19p13.13.

Furthermore, Congenital Dyserythropoietic Anemia Type IV is also known by several exact synonyms, including CDA IV, CDA due to KLF1 mutation, CDA type 4, CDA type IV, CDAN4, Congenital dyserythropoietic anaemia due to KLF1 mutation, Congenital dyserythropoietic anaemia type 4, Congenital dyserythropoietic anemia due to KLF1 mutation, and Congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type 4, as well as congenital dyserythropoietic anaemia type IV.

Congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type II is a type of congenital dyserythropoietic anemia, which is a specific form of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and involves abnormalities related to prenatal development or birth. This condition is defined as a congenital dyserythropoietic anemia characterized by a range from mild to severe anemia, the presence of bi- and multinucleated erythroblasts in the bone marrow, jaundice, splenomegaly, which may lead to liver iron overload and gallstones, and is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SEC23B gene on chromosome 20p11.23. Congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type II is also known by several exact synonyms: CDA II, CDA type 2, CDA type II, CDAN2, Congenital dyserythropoietic anaemia type 2, Congenital dyserythropoietic anemia type 2, Hereditary erythroblastic multinuclearity with a positive acidified-serum test (hempas), and SEC23B-CDG, along with its naming variation as congenital dyserythropoietic anaemia type II.

Mucopolysaccharidosis type IIID is a specific form of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the broader category of mucopolysaccharidosis III, and it inherently involves autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a mucopolysaccharidosis III that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GNS gene located on chromosome 12q14.3. This condition is precisely identified by several exact synonyms, including GNS deficiency, MPS IIID, MPS3D, Mucopolysaccharidosis type 3D, N-acetylglucosamine-6-sulfatase deficiency, Sanfilippo syndrome D, and Sanfilippo syndrome type D, highlighting its various recognized nomenclatures in the medical field.

Mega corpus callosum syndrome with cerebellar hypoplasia and cortical malformations (MCCCHCM) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of syndromic intellectual disability. It is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and exhibits a phenotype of neurodevelopmental delay. MCCCHCM is defined as a syndromic intellectual disability marked by global developmental delay, impaired intellectual development, and distinct brain abnormalities, which result from a heterozygous mutation in the MAST1 gene on chromosome 19p13.13.

Jalili syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which specifically has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by amelogenesis imperfecta and cone-rod retinal dystrophy, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in CNNM4 on chromosome 2q11.2. Furthermore, Jalili syndrome is exactly synonymous with Cone rod dystrophy-amelogenesis imperfecta syndrome and cone-rod dystrophy and amelogenesis imperfecta.

Fraser Syndrome 1 is a type of Fraser Syndrome which is defined as a Fraser Syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FRAS1 gene located on chromosome 4q21.21. Moreover, Fraser Syndrome 1 is exactly synonymous with FRASRS1.

Fraser syndrome 3 is a type of Fraser syndrome and is also known exactly as FRASRS3. It is defined as a Fraser syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GRIP1 gene on chromosome 12q14.3.

Fraser Syndrome 2 is a type of Fraser Syndrome and is also known as FRASRS2. It is defined as a Fraser Syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the FREM2 gene on chromosome 13q13.3.

Exudative vitreoretinopathy 5, also known exactly as EVR5, is a type of exudative vitreoretinopathy and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined by an exudative vitreoretinopathy that results from a heterozygous mutation in the TSPAN12 gene located on chromosome 7q31.31.

Exudative vitreoretinopathy 3 is a type of exudative vitreoretinopathy and an autosomal dominant disease, which at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an exudative vitreoretinopathy that has its material basis in heterozygous mutation in a region on chromosome 11p13-p12. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with EVR3.

Exudative vitreoretinopathy 6 is classified as a form of exudative vitreoretinopathy and is also recognized as an autosomal dominant disease, indicating it is one of the disorders that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined by an exudative vitreoretinopathy that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the ZNF408 gene located on chromosome 11p11.2. Additionally, it is precisely referred to by the exact synonym EVR6.

Exudative vitreoretinopathy 4, which is exactly synonymous with EVR4, is a type of exudative vitreoretinopathy and an autosomal genetic disease. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has its material basis in autosomal inheritance. Specifically, exudative vitreoretinopathy 4 is defined by an exudative vitreoretinopathy that arises from homozygous, compound heterozygous, or heterozygous mutations in the LRP5 gene located on chromosome 11q13.2.

Exudative vitreoretinopathy 1, also known exactly as EVR1, is a type of exudative vitreoretinopathy and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined by an exudative vitreoretinopathy that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the FZD4 gene located on chromosome 11q14.2.

X-linked exudative vitreoretinopathy 2 is a type of exudative vitreoretinopathy, which also falls under the category of X-linked monogenic diseases, and is a type of disorder that inherently has a material basis in some form of X-linked inheritance. This specific condition is defined as an exudative vitreoretinopathy that has its material basis in a mutation located in the NDP gene on chromosome Xp11.3. Furthermore, X-linked exudative vitreoretinopathy 2 is exactly synonymous with EVR2, EVRX, and FEVRX.

Trichohepatoenteric syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by intractable diarrhea, facial dysmorphism, immune abnormalities, and hair abnormalities, with liver and/or skin abnormalities seen in more than half of the cases. These symptoms are due to defects in components of the SKI complex. The syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: SD/THE, Syndromic diarrhea/Tricho-hepato-enteric syndrome, THES, Tricho-hepato-enteric syndrome, phenotypic diarrhea, and syndromic diarrhea.

Trichohepatoenteric syndrome 1 is a type of trichohepatoenteric syndrome and has an exact synonym, THES1. It is defined as a trichohepatoenteric syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TTC37 gene on chromosome 5q15.

Trichohepatoenteric syndrome 2 is a type of trichohepatoenteric syndrome, which is defined as a trichohepatoenteric syndrome that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SKIV2L gene on chromosome 6p21.33. Additionally, it has the exact synonym THES2.
Familial chylomicronemia syndrome is a type of familial hyperlipidemia, defined as a familial hyperlipidemia characterized by hypertriglyceridemia and fasting chylomicronemia.

Familial apolipoprotein C II deficiency is an autosomal recessive disease that falls under the category of familial chylomicronemia syndrome. It is characterized by a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is marked by the onset in adolescence or adulthood of hypertriglyceridemia and fasting chylomicronemia, which stems from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the APOC2 gene located on chromosome 19q13.32. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms, including C-II anapolipoproteinemia, familial APOC2 deficiency, familial apoC-II deficiency, hyperlipoproteinemia type 1b, and hyperlipoproteinemia type Ib.

Familial chylomicronemia due to inhibition of lipoprotein lipase activity is a type of familial chylomicronemia syndrome characterized by hypertriglyceridemia, chylomicronemia, very low levels of postheparin plasma lipolytic activity, the presence in the circulation of a lipoprotein lipase inhibitor, and elevated adipose levels of lipoprotein lipase.

Familial GPIHBP1 deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of familial chylomicronemia syndrome, which also inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is characterized by refractory fasting hyperchylomicronemia and elevated plasma triglyceride levels due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GPIHBP1 gene on chromosome 8q24.3. It is exactly synonymous with familial glycosylphosphatidylinositol-anchored high-density lipoprotein-binding protein 1 deficiency, hyperlipoproteinemia type 1D, and hyperlipoproteinemia type ID.

Familial apolipoprotein A5 deficiency is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of familial chylomicronemia syndrome, which further falls under the category of conditions that at least have a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition, synonymous with familial APOA5 deficiency and familial apolipoprotein A-V deficiency, is characterized as a familial chylomicronemia syndrome by hyperchylomicronemia, elevated levels of very low-density lipoprotein, and decreased LDL and HDL levels after fasting. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the APOA5 gene located on chromosome 11q23.3.

Familial lipase maturation factor 1 deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of familial chylomicronemia syndrome. It is a condition that fundamentally involves some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by hypertriglyceridemia, chylomicronemia, and decreased lipase activity due to a homozygous mutation in the LMF1 gene located on chromosome 16p13.3. Moreover, familial lipase maturation factor 1 deficiency is also known by several exact synonyms, including LPL and HL deficiency, LPL and HTGL deficiency, combined lipase deficiency, familial LMF1 deficiency, and lipoprotein lipase deficiency with hepatic triglyceride lipase deficiency.

Branchiootorenal syndrome 1 is a type of branchiootorenal syndrome and has the exact synonym BOR1. It is defined as a branchiootorenal syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the EYA1 gene on chromosome 8q13.3.

Branchiootorenal syndrome 2 is a type of branchiootorenal syndrome and has an exact synonym, BOR2. It is defined as a branchiootorenal syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SIX5 gene on chromosome 19q13.32.

Restrictive cardiomyopathy 1 is identified as a type of restrictive cardiomyopathy, defined by a restrictive cardiomyopathy that originates from a heterozygous mutation in the TNNI3 gene located on chromosome 19q13.42. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with RCM1 and familial restrictive cardiomyopathy 1.

Restrictive cardiomyopathy 2 is a type of restrictive cardiomyopathy that is defined as a restrictive cardiomyopathy with a material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 10q23.3. It is also exactly synonymous with RCM2 and familial restrictive cardiomyopathy 2.

Restrictive cardiomyopathy 3 is a type of restrictive cardiomyopathy, which is defined as a restrictive cardiomyopathy that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the TNNT2 gene on chromosome 1q32.1. Moreover, restrictive cardiomyopathy 3 is exactly synonymous with RCM3 and familial restrictive cardiomyopathy 3.

Essential Tremor 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is a subtype of essential tremor and is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an essential tremor that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DRD3 gene on chromosome 3q13.31. Furthermore, Essential Tremor 1 is exactly synonymous with ETM1 and hereditary essential tremor 1.

Essential Tremor 2 (ETM2), also known as Hereditary Essential Tremor 2, is a type of essential tremor and a kind of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically due to a heterozygous mutation in a region on chromosome 2p25-p22. This defines Essential Tremor 2 and emphasizes its genetic foundation.

Essential Tremor 3 is a type of essential tremor, which is defined as an essential tremor that has its material basis in variation in a region on chromosome 6p23. It is exactly synonymous with ETM3 and hereditary essential tremor 3.

Essential Tremor 4 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of essential tremor that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an essential tremor that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FUS gene on chromosome 16p11.2. Additionally, Essential Tremor 4 has the exact synonyms ETM4 and hereditary essential tremor 4.

Essential Tremor 5 (ETM5), also known as Hereditary Essential Tremor 5, is classified as a type of Essential Tremor and an Autosomal Dominant disease, indicating it is a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is specifically defined by an essential tremor that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TENM4 gene located on chromosome 11q14.1.

Optic atrophy 3, also known exactly as ADOAC, OPA3, autosomal dominant optic atrophy 3, autosomal dominant optic atrophy and cataract, autosomal dominant optic atrophy type 3, and optic atrophy 3 with cataract, is a type of optic atrophy and a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by optic atrophy and cataract, stemming from a heterozygous mutation in the OPA3 gene on chromosome 19q13.32. This condition is also identified as a type of entity that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Optic atrophy 10 is a type of optic atrophy and an autosomal dominant disease, also described as having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an optic atrophy characterized by early-onset optic neuropathy and mitochondrial defects, which is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RTN4IP1 gene on chromosome 6q21. Furthermore, optic atrophy 10 is exactly synonymous with OPA10 and also known as optic atrophy 10 with or without ataxia, mental retardation, and seizures.

Optic atrophy 6 is a type of optic atrophy and a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is further specified as something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.
