It is characterized by an early onset of slowly progressive isolated optic atrophy, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in a region on chromosome 8q21-q22. Additionally, optic atrophy 6 is exactly synonymous with OPA6.

Optic atrophy 11, also exactly synonymous with OPA11, is a type of optic atrophy and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that necessarily has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, optic atrophy 11 is defined as an optic atrophy marked by delayed psychomotor development, intellectual disability, ataxia, optic atrophy, and leukoencephalopathy consistent with mitochondrial dysfunction. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the YME1L1 gene located on chromosome 10p12.1.

Optic atrophy 7 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of optic atrophy, which fundamentally has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance patterns. It is characterized by juvenile onset, severe bilateral deficiency in visual acuity, optic disc pallor, and central scotoma, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TMEM126A gene located on chromosome 11q14.1. Additionally, optic atrophy 7 is precisely synonymous with OPA7 and also referred to as optic atrophy 7 with or without auditory neuropathy.

Optic atrophy 5, also exactly synonymous with OPA5, is classified as a type of optic atrophy and an autosomal dominant disease. It is specifically acknowledged as a condition that fundamentally originates from an autosomal dominant inheritance. Optic atrophy 5 is defined by the degeneration of retinal ganglion cells leading to a gradually progressive visual loss with a variable onset ranging from the first to the third decades, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the DNM1L gene located on chromosome 12p11.21.

Optic atrophy 8 is a type of optic atrophy and an autosomal dominant disease that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by progressive visual loss during the first or second decade of life, due to a heterozygous mutation in a region on chromosome 16q21-q22. Optic atrophy 8 is also precisely known as OPA8.

Optic atrophy 4 is classified as a type of optic atrophy and is a specific form of autosomal dominant disease, which broadly means it involves a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, optic atrophy 4 is defined by an optic atrophy that results from a heterozygous mutation in a region on chromosome 18q12.2-q12.3. Additionally, optic atrophy 4 is precisely referred to by the exact synonym OPA4.

Optic atrophy 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and optic atrophy, specifically characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an optic atrophy characterized by early childhood onset of visual impairment, temporal optic disc pallor, color vision deficits, and centrocecal scotoma of variable density, which has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the OPA1 gene on chromosome 3q29. Additionally, optic atrophy 1 has an exact synonym, OPA1.

Optic atrophy 9, also known exactly as OPA9, is a type of optic atrophy and autosomal recessive disease. This condition specifically arises from a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by an optic atrophy characterized by early childhood onset of decreased visual acuity, pallor of the optic discs, severely reduced visual acuity, paracentral scotoma, red-green dyschromatopsia, and temporal optic atrophy at the fundus. This is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ACO2 gene located on chromosome 22q13.2.

Optic atrophy 2 is a type of optic atrophy, which is defined as an optic atrophy that has its material basis in variation in a region on chromosome Xp11.4-p11.21. Additionally, optic atrophy 2 is exactly synonymous with OPA2 and X-linked optic atrophy 2.

Progressive Myoclonus Epilepsy 4 (PME4) is a specific type of disease classified under autosomal recessive diseases, progressive myoclonus epilepsy, and conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized as a progressive myoclonus epilepsy often associated with renal failure, with its material basis found in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SCARB2 gene on chromosome 4q21.1. PME4 is also known by exact synonyms such as AMRF, EPM4, Myoclonus-nephropathy syndrome, and Action myoclonus-renal failure syndrome.

Progressive myoclonus epilepsy 10 (EPM10), also known as early-onset Lafora body disease, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of progressive myoclonus epilepsy. This specific condition is characterized by the onset of progressive myoclonus, ataxia, spasticity, dysarthria, and cognitive decline within the first decade of life. It is further defined by its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PRDM8 gene located on chromosome 4q21.21. Additionally, it is a type of disorder that inherently involves some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Progressive Myoclonus Epilepsy 3 (PME3) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a category of progressive myoclonus epilepsy. It specifically belongs to a group of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. PME3 is characterized by the onset of intractable myoclonic seizures before the age of 2 years and developmental regression, caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KCTD7 gene on chromosome 7q11.21. This condition is known by several exact synonyms, including CLN14 disease, EPM3, PME type 3, Progressive myoclonic epilepsy due to KCTD7 deficiency, Progressive myoclonus epilepsy type 3, and neuronal ceroid lipofuscinosis 14.

Progressive myoclonus epilepsy 7 (PME7) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of progressive myoclonus epilepsy. It is characterized by an onset of severe progressive myoclonus and infrequent tonic-clonic seizures in the first or second decades of life, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the KCNC1 gene on chromosome 11p15.1. This condition is also synonymous with several other names, including EPM7, MEAK, Myoclonus epilepsy and ataxia due to potassium channel mutation, PME type 7, Progressive myoclonic epilepsy due to KV3.1 deficiency, and Progressive myoclonus epilepsy type 7, highlighting its association with autosomal dominant inheritance and its specific genetic basis.

Progressive myoclonus epilepsy 1b (EPM1B) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a form of Unverricht Lundborg syndrome. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PRICKLE1 gene located on chromosome 12q12.

Progressive myoclonus epilepsy 6 (PME6) is a specific type of progressive myoclonus epilepsy and is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease. It is defined by the onset of ataxia in the first years of life, followed by action myoclonus and seizures later in childhood, and the loss of independent ambulation in the second decade. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GOSR2 gene on chromosome 17q21.32. It is also known by several exact synonyms including EPM6, GOSR2-related progressive myoclonus ataxia, North Sea progressive myoclonus epilepsy, PME type 6, and Progressive myoclonus epilepsy type 6.

Progressive Myoclonus Epilepsy 9 (PME 9) is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is a subtype of progressive myoclonus epilepsy, and it is associated with a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. PME 9 is characterized by severe myoclonic and tonic-clonic seizures that start in childhood, along with early-onset ataxia. This condition specifically arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the LMNB2 gene located on chromosome 19p13.3. Moreover, PME 9 is also known by several exact synonyms, including EMP9, PME type 9, progressive myoclonic epilepsy due to LMNB2 deficiency, and progressive myoclonus epilepsy type 9.

Progressive Myoclonus Epilepsy 8 (PME8) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is categorized under progressive myoclonus epilepsy. It is characterized by a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, PME8 is defined as a progressive myoclonus epilepsy that typically begins in childhood to adolescence. It is marked by action myoclonus, generalized tonic-clonic seizures, and slowly progressive, moderate to severe cognitive impairment. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CERS1 gene located on chromosome 19p13.11. Moreover, Progressive Myoclonus Epilepsy 8 is also known by its exact synonyms: EMP8, PME type 8, progressive myoclonic epilepsy due to CERS1 deficiency, and progressive myoclonus epilepsy type 8.
